{"title_page": "Dantzig Alley British Cemetery", "text_new": "{{Infobox military memorial\n|name= Dantzig Alley British Cemetery\n|body= [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]\n|image=File:Dantzig Alley British Cemetery -21.JPG\n|image_size=300\n|use_dates=1916 \n|established=1916\n|designer= [[Herbert Baker]]\n|coordinates= {{coord|49.9994|2.7438 |format=dms|type:landmark_region:FR|display=inline,title}}\n|nearest_town= [[Mametz, Somme|Mametz]], [[Somme (department)|Somme]], [[France]]\n|total=2,053\n|unknowns= \n|by_country=[[Allies of World War I|Allied Powers]]:\n*[[United Kingdom]]: 1,494\n*[[New Zealand]]: 18\n*[[Australia]]: 13\n*[[Canada]]: 10\n*[[South Africa]]: 3\n*[[India]]: 1\n*Unknown: 518\n|by_war=\n[[First World War]]: 2,053\n|source=   \n}}\n\n'''Dantzig Alley British Cemetery''' is a [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] burial ground for the dead of the [[World War I|First World War]]. It is located near the village of [[Mametz, Somme|Mametz]], eight kilometres from [[Albert, Somme|Albert]] in the [[Somme (department)|Somme department]] of France.\n\n==History==\nThe village of [[Mametz, Somme|Mametz]] is located approximately eight kilometres to the east of [[Albert, Somme|Albert]]{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|p=308}} and on 1 July 1916, the opening day of the [[Battle of the Somme]], it was an objective for the British [[7th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|7th Division]], along with a nearby German trench named Dantzig Alley which ran to the southwest of Mametz. Both were captured by elements of the division's [[91st Brigade (United Kingdom)|91st Brigade]], the 22nd Battalion of the [[Manchester Regiment]] and the 1st Battalion of the [[South Staffordshire Regiment]].{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|pp=159\u2013160}}\n\n==Foundation==\nThe cemetery, named for the German trench, was established soon after Mametz was captured and used up until November 1916. The area remained in Allied hands until March 1918, when the Germans captured Mametz during the [[Spring Offensive]]. During the [[Hundred Days Offensive]] that commenced in August 1918 it was recaptured by the British.{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|pp=159\u2013160}}\n\nBy the end of the war, the Dantzig Alley British Cemetery held 183 graves; most contained men who had been killed in the early stages of the Battle of the Somme but a few were from the fighting in the area in 1918.{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|pp=159\u2013160}} The cemetery grew in the following years as it received the remains of soldier's originally interred in a number of smaller battlefield cemeteries in the area as these were consolidated. These smaller cemeteries included the Aeroplane, Bottom Wood and Hare Lane Cemeteries, all from around Fricourt, with several others from around Mametz.<ref name=CWGC/>\n\n==Cemetery==\nThe cemetery, designed by the English architect [[Herbert Baker]], is located just to the east of Mametz on the D64 Road to [[Montauban-de-Picardie|Montauban]].<ref name=CWGC/> It is situated on high ground and there are views of Mametz Wood,{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|p=161}} the scene of intense fighting in the days after Mametz village was captured.{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|p=313}} The entrance is at the southwest corner with a [[Stone of Remembrance]] just to the east, centrally arranged to the width of the cemetery. At the northern end of the cemetery, centrally positioned to its width, is a [[Cross of Sacrifice]].<ref name=CWGC/>\n\nThere are a number of special memorials to soldiers who are believed to be among the unidentified interments and other memorials for soldiers buried elsewhere but whose graves were destroyed by artillery during the war and these are arranged along the northern wall.<ref name=CWGC>{{cite web |title=Dantzig Alley British Cemetery |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/61000/dantzig-alley-british-cemetery,-mametz/ |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> There are also two memorials to soldiers of the [[Royal Welch Fusiliers]]; one for those who lost their lives on the Somme over the period 1916 to 1918 and the other to those killed in the fighting in Mametz Wood in July 1916.{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|p=161}}\n\nThe remains of 2,053 soldiers, with over 500 of them unidentified, are interred in the cemetery. Of the 1,535 identified interments, 1,493 are British, 18 are soldiers of the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]], and there are 13 personnel of the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]]. There are also ten Canadians, three South Africans and a sole soldier from [[British India|India]] buried in the cemetery.<ref name=CWGC/>\n\nNotable interments at Dantzig Alley British Cemetery include two professional footballers from the [[English Football League|Football League]], [[Charles Randall (footballer)|Charles Randall]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Casualty Record: Randall, Charles |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/548205/ |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Harold Meadowcroft]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Casualty Record: Meadowcroft, H. C. |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/548031/ |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Dantzig Alley British Cemetery -16.JPG|thumb|right|Dantzig Alley British Cemetery's Cross of Sacrifice]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gliddon|first=Gerald|title=Somme 1916: A Battlefield Campanion|year=2009|origyear=1987|publisher=The History Press|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire, United Kingdom|isbn=978-0-7524-5335-4|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{commons category|Dantzig Alley British Cemetery, Mametz}}\n\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in France]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Somme (department)]]\n[[Category:World War I cemeteries in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Military Cemetery\n|name= Dantzig Alley British Cemetery\n|body= [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]\n|image=File:Dantzig Alley British Cemetery -21.JPG\n|image_size=300\n|use_dates=1916 \n|established=1916\n|designer= [[Herbert Baker]]\n|coordinates= {{coord|49.9994|2.7438 |format=dms|type:landmark_region:FR|display=inline,title}}\n|nearest_town= [[Mametz, Somme|Mametz]], [[Somme (department)|Somme]], [[France]]\n|total=2,053\n|unknowns= \n|by_country=[[Allies of World War I|Allied Powers]]:\n*[[United Kingdom]]: 1,494\n*[[New Zealand]]: 18\n*[[Australia]]: 13\n*[[Canada]]: 10\n*[[South Africa]]: 3\n*[[India]]: 1\n*Unknown: 518\n|by_war=\n[[First World War]]: 2,053\n|source=   \n}}\n\n'''Dantzig Alley British Cemetery''' is a [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] burial ground for the dead of the [[World War I|First World War]]. It is located near the village of [[Mametz, Somme|Mametz]], eight kilometres from [[Albert, Somme|Albert]] in the [[Somme (department)|Somme department]] of France.\n\n==History==\nThe village of [[Mametz, Somme|Mametz]] is located approximately eight kilometres to the east of [[Albert, Somme|Albert]]{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|p=308}} and on 1 July 1916, the opening day of the [[Battle of the Somme]], it was an objective for the British [[7th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|7th Division]], along with a nearby German trench named Dantzig Alley which ran to the southwest of Mametz. Both were captured by elements of the division's [[91st Brigade (United Kingdom)|91st Brigade]], the 22nd Battalion of the [[Manchester Regiment]] and the 1st Battalion of the [[South Staffordshire Regiment]].{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|pp=159\u2013160}}\n\n==Foundation==\nThe cemetery, named for the German trench, was established soon after Mametz was captured and used up until November 1916. The area remained in Allied hands until March 1918, when the Germans captured Mametz during the [[Spring Offensive]]. During the [[Hundred Days Offensive]] that commenced in August 1918 it was recaptured by the British.{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|pp=159\u2013160}}\n\nBy the end of the war, the Dantzig Alley British Cemetery held 183 graves; most contained men who had been killed in the early stages of the Battle of the Somme but a few were from the fighting in the area in 1918.{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|pp=159\u2013160}} The cemetery grew in the following years as it received the remains of soldier's originally interred in a number of smaller battlefield cemeteries in the area as these were consolidated. These smaller cemeteries included the Areoplane, Bottom Wood and Hare Lane Cemeteries, all from around Fricourt, with several others from around Mametz.<ref name=CWGC/>\n\n==Cemetery==\nThe cemetery, designed by the English architect [[Herbert Baker]], is located just to the east of Mametz on the D64 Road to [[Montauban-de-Picardie|Montauban]].<ref name=CWGC/> It is situated on high ground and there are views of Mametz Wood,{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|p=161}} the scene of intense fighting in the days after Mametz village was captured.{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|p=313}} The entrance is at the southwest corner with a [[Stone of Remembrance]] just to the east, centrally arranged to the width of the cemetery. At the northern end of the cemetery, centrally positioned to its width, is a [[Cross of Sacrifice]].<ref name=CWGC/> \n\nThere are a number of special memorials to soldiers who are believed to be among the unidentified interments and other memorials for soldiers buried elsewhere but whose graves were destroyed by artillery during the war and these are arranged along the northern wall.<ref name=CWGC>{{cite web |title=Dantzig Alley British Cemetery |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/61000/dantzig-alley-british-cemetery,-mametz/ |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> There are also two memorials to soldiers of the [[Royal Welch Fusiliers]]; one for those who lost their lives on the Somme over the period 1916 to 1918 and the other to those killed in the fighting in Mametz Wood in July 1916.{{sfn|Gliddon|2009|p=161}}\n\nThe remains of 2,053 soldiers, with over 500 of them unidentified, are interred in the cemetery. Of the 1,535 identified interments, 1,493 are British, 18 are soldiers of the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]], and there are 13 personnel of the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]]. There are also ten Canadians, three South Africans and a sole soldier from [[British India|India]] buried in the cemetery.<ref name=CWGC/> \n\nNotable interments at Dantzig Alley British Cemetery include two professional footballers from the [[English Football League|Football League]], [[Charles Randall (footballer)|Charles Randall]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Casualty Record: Randall, Charles |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/548205/ |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Harold Meadowcroft]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Casualty Record: Meadowcroft, H. C. |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/548031/ |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Dantzig Alley British Cemetery -16.JPG|thumb|right|Dantzig Alley British Cemetery's Cross of Sacrifice]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gliddon|first=Gerald|title=Somme 1916: A Battlefield Campanion|year=2009|origyear=1987|publisher=The History Press|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire, United Kingdom|isbn=978-0-7524-5335-4|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{commonscat|Dantzig Alley British Cemetery, Mametz}}\n\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in France]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Somme (department)]]\n[[Category:World War I cemeteries in France]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: Areoplane \u2192 Aeroplane", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dantzig_Alley_British_Cemetery"}
{"title_page": "Kirateshwar Mahadev Temple", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n|name = Kirateshwar Mahadev Temple\n|image =Legship_shiva_temple.jpg\n|alt = \n|caption = Main Shrine of Kirateshwar Mahadev Temple\n|map_type = India Sikkim\n|coordinates = {{coord|27|27|N|88|27|E|type:landmark_region:IN-SK|display=inline,title}}\n|map_caption = Location in [[Sikkim]]\n| native_name = Shiv Mandir\n|country= [[India]]\n|state= [[Sikkim]]\n|district= [[Gyalshing]], [[West Sikkim]]\n| location  = [[Legship]]\n| deity  = [[Shiva]]\n| festivals= Bala Chaturdasi and [[Maha Shivaratri]] \n|architecture =\n}}\n'''Kirateshwar Mahadev Temple''' is a [[Hindu]] temple, identified to be a Hindu pilgrimage site which is located at [[Legship]], [[West Sikkim]], [[India]] along the banks of River [[Rangeet]].,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sikkim-culture.gov.in/Cultural%20Festivals/Religious%20Places.aspx | title = Some of the Religious Places of Sikkim | accessdate = 2011-12-15 | work = Cultural Affairs & Heritage Department | publisher = Government of Sikkim | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426051856/http://www.sikkim-culture.gov.in/Cultural%20Festivals/Religious%20Places.aspx | archivedate = 2012-04-26 }}</ref> which has many mythological episodes of the [[Mahabharata]] attached to it. The temple is also known as '''''Kirateshwar Mahadev Thaan'' by the  [[Kirati people]]''' or simply known as '''''Shiv Mandir'''''.\n\n==Main Attraction==\nThe main attraction of the temple are the festival of the [[Bala Chaturdashi]], which is observed in November\u2013December every year and the Shiv Ratri also known as [[Maha Shivaratri]] which falls in the month of February or March every year. There are other temples dedicated to Lord [[Rama]] and [[Durga]] can be found here making it an important pilgrimage destination for [[Hindu]]s.\n\n==Historical Background==\nAccording to [[Hindu]] beliefs, pleased with [[Arjuna]]'s hard penance and devotion, Lord [[Shiva]] appeared before him in the very spot where the temple lies as hunter ''Kirateshwar'' or ''Lord of the Kiratas'' and blessed him with success in the [[Kurukshetra War|Mahabharat War]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mapsofindia.com/sikkim/tourism/legship.html |title=Legship Sikkim |publisher=Mapsofindia.com |accessdate=2011-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130128050515/http://www.mapsofindia.com/sikkim/tourism/legship.html |archivedate=2013-01-28 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | title = Society and Economy of Sikkim Under Namgyal Rulers (1640-1890) | year = 2014 | last = Gautam| first = Keshav| pages = 10\u201311 }}</ref> Long time ago as the people found miraculously existed a stone manifesting [[Lingam|Shiva Ling]]. The said Shiv Ling is the main effigy of worship. Belief of many that a mere visit with true devotion to this temple fulfills one's wishes particularly a wish for son or daughter and also wishes for peace harmony and good health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gopelling.net/legship_rangeet%20Rivedam_kirateswar_mahadev_mandir_reshi_hotspring.html |title=Legship Rangeet River dam, Kirateswar Mahadev Mandir, Reshi hot spring |publisher=www.gopelling.net |date= | accessdate=2015-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kirata]]\n* [[Kirata Kingdom]]\n* [[Kirati people]]\n* [[Kirat Mundhum]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Mahabharata}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Hindu temples in Sikkim}}\n\n[[Kirat Mundhum]]\n\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Sikkim]]\n[[Category:West Sikkim district]]\n\n\n{{India-hindu-temple-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n|name = Kirateshwar Mahadev Temple\n|image =Legship_shiva_temple.jpg\n|alt = \n|caption = Main Shrine of Kirateshwar Mahadev Temple\n|map_type = India Sikkim\n|coordinates = {{coord|27|27|N|88|27|E|type:landmark_region:IN-SK|display=inline,title}}\n|map_caption = Location in [[Sikkim]]\n| native_name = Shiv Mandir\n|country= [[India]]\n|state= [[Sikkim]]\n|district= [[Gyalshing]], [[West Sikkim]]\n| location  = [[Legship]]\n| deity  = [[Lord Shiva]]\n| festivals= Bala Chaturdasi and [[Maha Shivaratri]] \n|architecture =\n}}\n'''Kirateshwar Mahadev Temple''' is a [[Hindu]] temple, identified to be a Hindu pilgrimage site which is located at [[Legship]], [[West Sikkim]], [[India]] along the banks of River [[Rangeet]].,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sikkim-culture.gov.in/Cultural%20Festivals/Religious%20Places.aspx | title = Some of the Religious Places of Sikkim | accessdate = 2011-12-15 | work = Cultural Affairs & Heritage Department | publisher = Government of Sikkim | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426051856/http://www.sikkim-culture.gov.in/Cultural%20Festivals/Religious%20Places.aspx | archivedate = 2012-04-26 }}</ref> which has many mythological episodes of the [[Mahabharata]] attached to it. The temple is also known as '''''Kirateshwar Mahadev Thaan'' by the  [[Kirati people]]''' or simply known as '''''Shiv Mandir'''''.\n\n==Main Attraction==\nThe main attraction of the temple are the festival of the [[Bala Chaturdashi]], which is observed in November\u2013December every year and the Shiv Ratri also known as [[Maha Shivaratri]] which falls in the month of February or March every year. There are other temples dedicated to Lord [[Rama]] and [[Durga]] can be found here making it an important pilgrimage destination for [[Hindu]]s.\n\n==Historical Background==\nAccording to [[Hindu]] beliefs, pleased with [[Arjuna]]'s hard penance and devotion, Lord [[Shiva]] appeared before him in the very spot where the temple lies as hunter ''Kirateshwar'' or ''Lord of the Kiratas'' and blessed him with success in the [[Kurukshetra War|Mahabharat War]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mapsofindia.com/sikkim/tourism/legship.html |title=Legship Sikkim |publisher=Mapsofindia.com |accessdate=2011-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130128050515/http://www.mapsofindia.com/sikkim/tourism/legship.html |archivedate=2013-01-28 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | title = Society and Economy of Sikkim Under Namgyal Rulers (1640-1890) | year = 2014 | last = Gautam| first = Keshav| pages = 10\u201311 }}</ref> Long time ago as the people found miraculously existed a stone manifesting [[Lingam|Shiva Ling]]. The said Shiv Ling is the main effigy of worship. Belief of many that a mere visit with true devotion to this temple fulfills one's wishes particularly a wish for son or daughter and also wishes for peace harmony and good health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gopelling.net/legship_rangeet%20Rivedam_kirateswar_mahadev_mandir_reshi_hotspring.html |title=Legship Rangeet River dam, Kirateswar Mahadev Mandir, Reshi hot spring |publisher=www.gopelling.net |date= | accessdate=2015-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kirata]]\n* [[Kirata Kingdom]]\n* [[Kirati people]]\n* [[Kirat Mundhum]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Mahabharata}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Hindu temples in Sikkim}}\n\n[[Kirat Mundhum]]\n\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Sikkim]]\n[[Category:West Sikkim district]]\n\n\n{{India-hindu-temple-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirateshwar_Mahadev_Temple"}
{"title_page": "Antonio Fabr\u00e9 y Almer\u00e1s", "text_new": "'''Antonio Fabr\u00e9 y Almer\u00e1s''' was an 18th-century [[Spain|Spanish]] [[monk]], writer and [[numismatics|numismatist]]. He was born in the province of [[C\u00e1diz (province)|C\u00e1diz]] in 1728 and died in [[Rota, C\u00e1diz]], in 1806.\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fabre y Almeras, Antonio}}\n[[Category:Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish numismatists]]\n[[Category:1728 births]]\n[[Category:1806 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish Christian monks]]\n[[Category:18th-century Spanish writers]]\n[[Category:People from C\u00e1diz]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n\n\n{{Spain-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Antonio Fabr\u00e9 y Almer\u00e1s''' was an 18th-century [[Spain|Spanish]] [[monk]], writer and [[numismatics|numismatist]]. He was born in the province of [[C\u00e1diz (province)|C\u00e1diz]] in 1728 and died in [[Rota, C\u00e1diz]], in 1806.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fabre y Almeras, Antonio}}\n[[Category:Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish numismatists]]\n[[Category:1728 births]]\n[[Category:1806 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish Christian monks]]\n[[Category:18th-century Spanish writers]]\n[[Category:People from C\u00e1diz]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n\n\n{{Spain-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Fabr%C3%A9_y_Almer%C3%A1s"}
{"title_page": "KZSF", "text_new": "{{short description|Regional Mexican radio station in San Jose, California}}\n{{Infobox Radio station\n| name             = KZSF\n| image            = KZSF logo.svg\n| city             = [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]]\n| area             = [[San Francisco Bay Area]]\n| slogan           = La Mejor Estacion de Radio en toda la Area De La Bahia\n| branding         = La Kaliente\n| frequency        = 1370 [[kHz]]\n| airdate          = {{start date and age|1947|6|21}} (as KEEN)\n| share            = \n| share as of      =  \n| share source     =  \n| format           = [[Regional Mexican]]\n| power            = 5,000 [[watt]]s\n| class            = B\n| facility_id      = 68841\n| coordinates      = {{nowrap|{{coord|37|21|28|N|121|52|17|W|region:US_type:city}}}}\n| callsign_meaning = Previous \"'''Z'''\" branding, '''S'''an '''F'''rancisco\n| former_callsigns = KEEN (1947\u20131993)<br>KKSJ (1993\u20131998)\n| owner            = Carlos A. Duharte\n| licensee         = \n| sister_stations  =\n| webcast          = [https://lakaliente1370am.com/live-radio/ Listen Live]\n| website          = [https://lakaliente1370am.com/ lakaliente1370am.com]\n| affiliations     = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n}}\n\n'''KZSF''' (1370 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) is a broadcast [[radio station]] in the United States. Licensed to [[San Jose, California]], KZSF serves the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] and has a [[regional Mexican]] music format branded \"La Kaliente 1370 AM.\" The station has been owned by Carlos A. Duharte since 2001.\n\nFor much of its history, KZSF has been a music radio station. Founded by [[George Mardikian]] and United Broadcasting Company, the station signed on with call sign KEEN in 1947 and operated out of the historic [[Hotel De Anza]] in San Jose for its first 27 years. After beginning with a general [[Full-service radio|full service]] format, KEEN became a [[country music|country and western]] station in the mid-1950s and would retain that format for over 35 years, with performers such as [[Red Murrell]] and [[Foy Willing]] among its on-air hosts. KEEN also featured live sports coverage; it broadcast the [[San Jose State Spartans]] and [[Santa Clara Broncos]] in the late 1950s and throughout the 1960s and the [[Oakland Athletics]] during the early to mid-1970s.\n\nIn 1993, KEEN went [[dark (broadcasting)|silent]] for several months after losing its transmitter license and returned to the air in 1994 as KKSJ and a [[pop standards]] format branded \"Magic 1370.\" Founding owner United Broadcasting sold the station in 1997. After one year with an Asian ethnic format, KKSJ became KZSF in 1998 and took on its present [[regional Mexican]] music format. KZSF would be sold twice more in the late 1990s before finally being purchased by Duharte in 2001.\n\n==History==\n===As KEEN (1947\u20131993)===\nFounded by United Broadcasting Company, whose president was [[George Mardikian]], KZSF came on the air in 1947 as a 1,000 watt station with call sign KEEN and a transmitter on a [[North San Jose]] orchard near the town border with [[Milpitas, California|Milpitas]].<ref name=\"Bay Area Radio Museum\"/><ref name=\"1948 yearbook\">{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1948/Radio%20by%20State%20BC%20YB%201948%20B&W-10.pdf|title=Directory of standard broadcasting stations in the United States|work=Broadcasting Telecasting 1948 Yearbook Number|place=Washington, DC|publisher=Broadcasting Publications|year=1948|page=92|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> KEEN was first granted a [[construction permit]] by the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) in 1945.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=37512 History Cards for KZSF], fcc.gov. Retrieved June 22, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"FCC data\">https://fccdata.org/?facid=&call=KZSF</ref> At 8 p.m. on June 21, 1947, KEEN's grand opening broadcast took place at the [[Hotel De Anza]] in [[Downtown San Jose]] and featured comedian [[Red Skelton]].<ref name=\"Bay Area Radio Museum\">{{cite web|url=https://bayarearadio.org/photos/farr/keen_grand-opening_june-1947|title=KEEN radio, San Jose Grand Opening Broadcast|publisher=Bay Area Radio Museum|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Two months later, KEEN was officially licensed by the FCC on August 21.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> In its early years, KEEN broadcast a [[Full-service radio|full service]] format with popular music, news, and sports.<ref name=\"Beilharz\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KhvHDwAAQBAJ|last=Beilharz|first=Edwin A.|last2=DeMers|first2=Donald O. Jr.|title=KBAY/KEEN: Broadcasting to serve their community|work=San Jose: California's First City|place=Tulsa, Oklahoma|publisher=Continental Heritage Press|year=1980|isbn=0932986137|via=Google Books}}</ref> Programming included news from the [[United Press International#History|United Press]],<ref name=\"1948 yearbook\"/> Saturday night [[barn dance|barn dances]],<ref>{{citation|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=11023&context=spartandaily|title='540' boys to play for barn dance|work=Spartan Daily|page=2|publisher=San Jose State College|date=January 16, 1948|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> and [[Santa Clara Broncos baseball|University of Santa Clara baseball]] games.<ref>{{citation|url=https://content.scu.edu/digital/collection/broncoseg/id/6102/rec/1|title=The Bull Pen|last=Winklebleck|first=Sam H.|work=The Santa Clara|publisher=University of Santa Clara|date=March 9, 1949|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>  By 1954, KEEN had a [[country music|country and western music]] format featuring hosts like [[Red Murrell]], [[Cal Smith]], and [[Foy Willing]].<ref name=\"Beilharz\"/><ref name=\"Bay Area Radio Museum\"/><ref name=\"Singleton\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5JaoGKu3OOUC&pg=PA113|title=Centerville, Fremont|last=Singleton|first=Jill M.|last2=Holmes|first2=Philip|page=113|place=Charleston, South Carolina|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2011|isbn=9780738581774|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/cal-smith-mn0000647518/biography|title=Cal Smith|last=Manheim|first=James|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> KEEN began broadcasting [[San Jose State Spartans football|San Jose State College football]] games in 1956.<ref>{{citation|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=12399&context=spartandaily|title=Bronzan, Team In Hawaii Finale|work=Spartan Daily|publisher=San Jose State College|volume=44|issue=44|page=3|date=November 30, 1956}}</ref> \n\nOn September 19, 1957, KEEN was granted a license for a new transmitter with a stronger daytime broadcasting power of 5,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> By 1960, KEEN added [[San Jose State Spartans men's basketball|San Jose State basketball]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=4099&context=spartandaily|title=KEEN airs tilts|work=Spartan Daily|date=December 2, 1960|volume=48|issue=45|page=4|publisher=San Jose State College|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The following year, KEEN began broadcasting select [[Santa Clara Broncos men's basketball|Santa Clara basketball]] games.<ref>{{citation|url=https://content.scu.edu/digital/collection/broncoseg/id/28961|title=Holiday Games Feature WCAC Tourney at SF|work=The Santa Clara|date=December 14, 1961|page=7|publisher=University of Santa Clara|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 1963, United Broadcasting launched a sister station that played [[pop standards]], [[KBRG|KEEN-FM]], on 100.3 MHz.<ref name=\"Beilharz\"/><ref name=\"Billboard 1966\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5SgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26|title=Stations by format|work=Billboard|date=March 26, 1966|volume=78|issue=13|page=26}}</ref> KEEN began broadcasting at its current power level of 5,000 watts at both day and night on August 26, 1964.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> By 1966, KEEN began playing selections from comedy records in addition to country music.<ref name=\"Billboard 1966\"/> The two KEEN stations no longer shared call letters in 1967, as KEEN-FM became KBAY.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1967/1967-03-13-BC.pdf|title=Call letter actions|work=Broadcasting|page=84|volume=72|issue=11|date=March 13, 1967|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> KEEN expanded its live sports play-by-play to include [[Santa Clara Broncos football|Santa Clara football]] in 1969.<ref>{{citation|last=Merolla|first=Vic|title=Broncs Face Long Beach State Tough Offense and Defense|url=https://content.scu.edu/digital/collection/broncoseg/id/8986/rec/14|work=The Santa Clara|publisher=University of Santa Clara|date=October 24, 1969|accessdate=March 27, 2020|page=1}}</ref>\n\nThe 1970s marked several changes for KEEN. Murrell left KEEN in 1970 after 16 years.<ref name=\"Singleton\"/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g6kwDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140|title=Workin' Man Blues: Country Music in California|last=Haslam|first=Gerald W.|last2=Russell|first2=Alexandra Haslam|last3=Chon|first3=Richard|place=Berkeley, California|publisher=University of California Press|year=1999|isbn=9780520275058|page=140|via=Google Books}}</ref> After the 1970\u201371 season, KEEN phased out its live college sports coverage in favor of pro sports. Santa Clara sports broadcasts moved to Los Altos FM station [[KJLV (FM)|KPEN]],<ref>{{citation|url=https://content.scu.edu/digital/collection/broncoseg/id/6469|title=Defense Prepares For Rebel Attack|last=Chipp|first=Steve|work=The Santa Clara|publisher=University of Santa Clara|date=October 8, 1971|accessdate=March 27, 2020|page=4}}</ref> and San Jose State broadcasts also moved to FM on Santa Clara's [[KVVN|KREP]].<ref>{{citation|last=Osterman|first=Tim|title=Spartans try Long Beach in crucial PCAA encounter|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=5546&context=spartandaily|work=Spartan Daily|publisher=San Jose State College|date=October 8, 1971|page=7|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> From 1971 to 1975, KEEN was the flagship station of the [[Oakland Athletics Radio Network|Oakland A's Radio Network]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Oakland Athletics Baseball On The Radio |url=https://bayarearadio.org/sports-index/athletics |website=Bay Area Radio Museum |date=13 August 2014}}</ref> KEEN also broadcast [[California Golden Seals]] games until the team moved out of the Bay Area in 1976.<ref>{{cite web |title=California Golden Seals Radio Coverage Map (1974-75) |url=https://bayarearadio.org/keen/seals_coverage-map |website=Bay Area Radio Museum |date=9 August 2014}}</ref> After over 25 years operating out of Hotel De Anza, United Broadcasting moved the KEEN and KBAY to [[West San Jose]] in 1974, on the top floor of the Golden Pacific Building at Winchester Boulevard.<ref name=\"Beilharz\"/> \n\nBy 1976, KEEN began playing newer country singles on weekday afternoons while focusing on [[classic country]] for the rest of the day.<ref>{{citation|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=6054&context=spartandaily|title=Radio stations offer variety|last=Burns|first=Robert|date=March 9, 1976|page=5|work=Spartan Daily|publisher=San Jose State University|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Following a request filed in 1979, the FCC approved the relocation of KEEN's studios to [[Campbell, California|Campbell]] in 1982.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=37689 FCC Application Search Details:   BML-19820104AH] (click \"Public Notice Comment\")</ref>\n\nBy January 1992, KEEN faced declining ratings and advertising revenue due to competition from FM stations, including new FM country station [[KRTY]].<ref name=\"gets the shaft\"/><ref name=\"Billboard 1995\"/> These factors led United Broadcasting to announce that KEEN would be a simulcast of easy listening FM sister station KBAY.<ref name=\"gets the shaft\">{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF5058366689603&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=KEEN's country gets the shaft|last=Weimers|first=Leigh|work=San Jose Mercury News|page=1D|date=January 22, 1992|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref> However, following much feedback from listeners and advertisers, United Broadcasting reversed this decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF505838EFCDCE0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=KEEN is back in the saddle again|last=Weimers|first=Leigh|date=January 31, 1992|page=1D|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref> However, beginning April 1 that year, KEEN cut its on-air staff to three hosts during daytime hours and broadcast [[broadcast syndication|syndicated]] music by satellite in other time slots.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF5058581FC6AA3&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=Place your bets: Do casinos help economy or not?|last=Weimers|first=Leigh|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=March 27, 1992|page=1E|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref> KEEN went [[dark (broadcasting)|off the air]] on January 1, 1993, after losing its transmitter lease a month earlier as the city of San Jose planned to build nearly 250 houses in the area.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weimers|first=Leigh|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF5058E553726FB&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=Country fans do a two-step with luck, good and bad|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=December 18, 1992|page=1D|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref><ref name=\"1976 transmitter\">{{cite web|url=https://bayarearadio.org/keen/keen_xmtr-bldg_1976|title=KEEN radio, San Jose, Transmitter Site circa 1976|publisher=Bay Area Radio Museum|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===As KKSJ (1993\u20131998)===\nOn October 11, 1993, KEEN became KKSJ.<ref name=\"FCC data\"/><ref name=\"Billboard 1995\">{{citation|last=Boehlert|first=Eric|title=Revived Station Trades Country Tunes for Sinatra|work=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7AsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA87&dq=KEEN+%22San+jose%22+country&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiF086x4bvoAhWBbc0KHQ9ECHgQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=KEEN%20%22San%20jose%22%20country&f=false|date=March 25, 1995|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Google Books}}</ref> After United Broadcasting made an arrangement for KKSJ to share the transmitter site near [[U.S. Highway 101]], a [[Union Pacific Railroad]] overpass, and an [[Eggo]] factory with fellow San Jose AM station [[KSJX]], KKSJ resumed broadcasting in 1994 with the brand \"Magic 1370\" and a [[pop standards]] format inspired by the former \"Magic 61\" brand of San Francisco's [[KEAR (AM)|KFRC]].<ref name=\"1976 transmitter\"/><ref name=\"Billboard 1995\"/> \"Magic 1370\" had a playlist from a 1,700-song library, including nearly 175 [[Frank Sinatra]] songs and others by artists including [[Ella Fitzgerald]] and [[Tony Bennett]].<ref name=\"Billboard 1995\"/> [[Jim Lange]], former KFRC DJ and host of ''[[The Dating Game]]'', joined KKSJ as a weekend host.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF7567C8A4A0E23&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=Jim Lange has a date in San Jose|last=Kava|first=Brad|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=August 12, 1994|page=Eye 20|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref>\n\nKKSJ rose from being unranked in the winter 1994 [[Arbitron]] Bay Area ratings to a 2.9 share by the fall of 1994.<ref name=\"Billboard 1995\"/> Lange left KKSJ in 1996.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB72068F39163A2&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=KABL tunes into big-band format and adds big-name DJs|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=January 28, 1997|last=Kava|first=Brad|page=10E|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1997, United Broadcasting sold KKSJ and KBAY to American Radio Systems for a combined $31.2 million.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1997/BC-1997-02-03.pdf|title=Station & Cable Trading|work=Broadcasting & Cable|volume=127|issue=5|date=February 3, 1997|page=32|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> American Radio subsequently laid off two hosts and dropped the locally programmed music for the syndicated [[Timeless (radio network)|Stardust]] music service.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF8576E14A8BDEF&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|last=Kava|first=Brad|title=Pondering local moves by corporate radio|work=San Jose Mercury News|page=Eye 20|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref> American Radio sold KKSJ to Douglas Broadcasting for $3.2 million in June 1997 and changed it to an Asian ethnic format with [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] and [[Cantonese]] programming.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Business-Report/Radio-Business-Report/1997/RBR-1997-06-30.pdf|title=Transaction Digest|work=Radio Business Report|date=June 30, 1997|volume=14|issue=26|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF857741739CFB5&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=KKSJ changes format - Sorkin wants new home|last=Kava|first=Brad|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=June 6, 1997|page=Eye 26|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref>\n\n===As KZSF (1998\u2013present)===\nOn January 20, 1998, the station changed its call sign to the current KZSF and entered a [[local marketing agreement]] to be a San Francisco Bay Area affiliate of [[Bustos Media|Amador Bustos]]'s Z-Spanish Radio Network of [[regional Mexican]] music stations, alongside sister station [[KREV (FM)|KZSF-FM]] in Alameda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=68841&Callsign=KZSF |title=KZSF Call Sign History |work=Federal Communications Commission }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1998-01.pdf|title=Format Changes & Updates|work=The M Street Journal|date=January 14, 1998|volume=15|issue=2|page=1|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980703020907/http://www.zspanish.com/p0000022.htm|archivedate=July 3, 1998|url=http://zspanish.com/p0000022.htm|title=Radio Stations|publisher=Z-Spanish Radio Network|accessdate=March 27, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bustos bought KZSF and five other stations from Douglas Broadcasting for $27 million in June 1998.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1999/BC-1999-02-15.pdf|title=Dealing for Dollars: TV and radio top sellers in 1998|work=Broadcasting & Cable|page=55|date=February 15, 1999|volume=129|issue=7|accessdate=March 28, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1998/BC-1998-07-06.pdf|title=Z-Spanish merging with Achievement Radio Holdings|work=Broadcasting & Cable|page=48|volume=128|issue=28|date=July 6, 1998|accessdate=March 28, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> For the first time since 1982 as KEEN, KZSF operated in San Jose, with a new location at Wooster Avenue near [[North San Jose]].<reF>{{cite book|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1999/D-Radio-All-BC-YB-1999..pdf|title=Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 1999|page=D-61|place=New Providence, New Jersey|publisher=R.R. Bowker|year=1999|isbn=0835241114|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> In June 2001, Carlos Duharte bought KZSF for $5 million and relocated the station to Tisch Way in West San Jose.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Business-Report/Radio-Business-Report/2001/RBR-2001-07-02.pdf|title=Transaction Digest|last=Seyler|first=Dave|last2=Messmer|first2=Dave|work=Radio Business Report|date=July 2, 2001|page=14|volume=18|issue=27|accessdate=March 28, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2001/D-Radio-All-BC-YB-2001.pdf|title=Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 2001|page=D-62|place=New Providence, New Jersey|publisher=Bowker|year=2001|isbn=0835243869|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref>\n\nWith its 1998 change to regional Mexican, KZSF added Spanish-language broadcasts of local sports teams, the [[San Francisco Giants]] baseball team and [[San Jose Earthquakes|San Jose Clash (later Earthquakes]] soccer team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Silent-treatment-for-fans-3054689.php|title=Silent treatment for fans|last=Smith|first=Michelle|work=San Francisco Examiner|date=July 8, 2000|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/19981207002003/http://www.clash.com/schedule/index.html</ref> However, the number of Giants games on the station declined from 81 home games in 1999 and 2000 to 40 in 2001 due to the Giants' inability to find advertisers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/article/Missing-in-translation-Spanish-baseball-2566011.php|title=Missing in translation / Spanish baseball broadcasts a tough sell in Bay Area|last=Ortiz|first=Jorge L.|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=July 10, 2003|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> After a hiatus, KZSF resumed Spanish broadcasts of Earthquakes games in 2004 and 2005 before resuming the broadcasts long term beginning in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/post/2010/03/24/english-and-spanish-broadcasts-2010|title=English and Spanish Broadcasts in 2010|publisher=San Jose Earthquakes|date=March 24, 2010|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/post/2013/02/12/kliv-kzsf-return-earthquakes-broadcast-partners|title=KLIV, KZSF return as Earthquakes broadcast partners|publisher=San Jose Earthquakes|date=February 12, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Earthquakes 2018\"/>\n\nUntil April 2002, KZSF was branded \"1370 AM La Z.\"<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20020422095151/http://www.1370am.com/</ref> In May 2002, KZSF changed its branding to \"La Kaliente.\"<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20020525093626/http://www.1370am.com:80/</ref>\n\nFrom 2004 to 2005, KZSF broadcast [[Oakland Raiders]] games in Spanish, before those broadcasts moved to [[KLOK (AM)|KLOK]] in 2006.<ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20041211095651/http://raidersenespanol.com/multimedia/radio.jsp</ref><ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20060908085430/http://www.raidersenespanol.com/multimedia/radio.jsp</ref> KZSF rejoined the Oakland A's Radio Network in 2005, broadcasting 48 games in Spanish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/shea/article/A-S-NOTEBOOK-Team-sale-won-t-be-delayed-by-2723093.php|title=A'S NOTEBOOK / Team sale won't be delayed by House steroid hearings|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=March 16, 2005|accessdate=March 29, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050419161608/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2005/03/16/SPGGEBQ3MO1.DTL|archivedate=April 19, 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> KZSF resumed broadcasting Raiders games in Spanish from 2009 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raiders.com/news/raiders-team-up-with-la-kaliente-710861|title= Raiders Team Up with La Kaliente |publisher=Oakland Raiders|date=July 28, 2009|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raiders.com/news/raiders-se-enfocan-en-delfines-3078868|title= Raiders Se Enfocan En Delfines |publisher=Oakland Raiders|date=November 23, 2010|accessdate=March 29, 2020|language=Spanish}}</reF>\n\n==Programming==\nOn weekdays, KZSF broadcasts a variety of Mexican music, including a nightly program dedicated to [[corrido|corridos]] and [[ranchera]], along with Spanish-language public affairs, advice, and sports talk shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lakaliente1370am.com/horario/|title=Programacion|publisher=La Kaliente 1370 AM|accessdate=March 29, 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> Celina Rodriguez, a former news anchor for local TV stations [[KDTV]] and [[KSTS]], has hosted a talk show on KZSF since 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2006/10/02/popular-anchor-moving-to-radio/|title=Popular anchor moving to radio|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=October 2, 2006|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ktvu.com/news/spanish-radio-host-using-airwaves-to-inform-how-to-help-those-suffering-from-mexico-city-quake|title=Spanish radio host using airwaves to inform how to help those suffering from Mexico City quake|publisher=KTVU|accessdate=March 29, 2020|date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> Additionally, KZSF carries Spanish-language broadcasts of [[San Jose Earthquakes]] games.<ref name=\"Earthquakes 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/post/2018/02/28/news-knbr-1050-1370-kzsf-continue-home-quakes-radio-broadcasts|title=NEWS: KNBR 1050, 1370 KZSF to Continue as Home for Quakes Radio Broadcasts|publisher=San Jose Earthquakes|date=February 28, 2018|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|KZSF}}\n\n{{San Jose Radio}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in California|ZSF]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in the San Francisco Bay Area|ZSF]]\n[[Category:Regional Mexican radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1947]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language radio stations in California|ZSF]]\n[[Category:1947 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Media in San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:California Golden Seals broadcasters]]\n[[Category:San Jose State Spartans football broadcasters]]\n[[Category:San Jose State Spartans men's basketball]]\n[[Category:Santa Clara Broncos football]]\n[[Category:Santa Clara Broncos men's basketball]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Giants broadcasters]]\n[[Category:San Jose Earthquakes broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders broadcasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Regional Mexican radio station in San Jose, California}}\n{{Infobox Radio station\n| name             = KZSF\n| image            = KZSF logo.svg\n| city             = [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]]\n| area             = [[San Francisco Bay Area]]\n| slogan           = La Mejor Estacion de Radio en toda la Area De La Bahia\n| branding         = La Kaliente\n| frequency        = 1370 [[kHz]]\n| airdate          = {{start date and age|1947|6|21}} (as KEEN)\n| share            = \n| share as of      =  \n| share source     =  \n| format           = [[Regional Mexican]]\n| power            = 5,000 [[watt]]s\n| class            = B\n| facility_id      = 68841\n| coordinates      = {{nowrap|{{coord|37|21|28|N|121|52|17|W|region:US_type:city}}}}\n| callsign_meaning = Previous \"'''Z'''\" branding, '''S'''an '''F'''rancisco\n| former_callsigns = KEEN (1947\u20131993)<br>KKSJ (1993\u20131998)\n| owner            = Carlos A. Duharte\n| licensee         = \n| sister_stations  =\n| webcast          = [https://lakaliente1370am.com/live-radio/ Listen Live]\n| website          = [https://lakaliente1370am.com/ lakaliente1370am.com]\n| affiliations     = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n}}\n\n'''KZSF''' (1370 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) is a broadcast [[radio station]] in the United States. Licensed to [[San Jose, California]], KZSF serves the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] and has a [[regional Mexican]] music format branded \"La Kaliente 1370 AM.\" The station has been owned by Carlos A. Duharte since 2001.\n\nFor much of its history, KZSF has been a music radio station. Founded by [[George Mardikian]] and United Broadcasting Company, the station signed on with call sign KEEN in 1947 and operated out of the historic [[Hotel De Anza]] in San Jose for its first 27 years. After beginning with a general [[Full-service radio|full service]] format, KEEN became a [[country music|country and western]] station in the mid-1950s and would retain that format for over 35 years, with performers such as [[Red Murrell]] and [[Foy Willing]] among its on-air hosts. KEEN also featured live sports coverage; it broadcast the [[San Jose State Spartans]] and [[Santa Clara Broncos]] in the late 1950s and throughout the 1960s and the [[Oakland Athletics]] during the early to mid-1970s.\n\nIn 1993, KEEN went [[dark (broadcasting)|silent]] for several months after losing its transmitter license and returned to the air in 1994 as KKSJ and a [[pop standards]] format branded \"Magic 1370.\" Founding owner United Broadcasting sold the station in 1997. After one year with an Asian ethnic format, KKSJ became KZSF in 1998 and took on its present [[regional Mexican]] music format. KZSF would be sold twice more in the late 1990s before finally being purchased by Duharte in 2001.\n\n==History==\n===As KEEN (1947\u20131993)===\nFounded by United Broadcasting Company, whose president was [[George Mardikian]], KZSF came on the air in 1947 as a 1,000 watt station with call sign KEEN and a transmitter on a [[North San Jose]] orchard near the town border with [[Milpitas, California|Milpitas]].<ref name=\"Bay Area Radio Museum\"/><ref name=\"1948 yearbook\">{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1948/Radio%20by%20State%20BC%20YB%201948%20B&W-10.pdf|title=Directory of standard broadcasting stations in the United States|work=Broadcasting Telecasting 1948 Yearbook Number|place=Washington, DC|publisher=Broadcasting Publications|year=1948|page=92|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> KEEN was first granted a [[construction permit]] by the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) in 1945.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=37512 History Cards for KZSF], fcc.gov. Retrieved June 22, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"FCC data\">https://fccdata.org/?facid=&call=KZSF</ref> At 8 p.m. on June 21, 1947, KEEN's grand opening broadcast took place at the [[Hotel De Anza]] in [[Downtown San Jose]] and featured comedian [[Red Skelton]].<ref name=\"Bay Area Radio Museum\">{{cite web|url=https://bayarearadio.org/photos/farr/keen_grand-opening_june-1947|title=KEEN radio, San Jose Grand Opening Broadcast|publisher=Bay Area Radio Museum|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Two months later, KEEN was officially licensed by the FCC on August 21.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> In its early years, KEEN broadcast a [[Full-service radio|full service]] format with popular music, news, and sports.<ref name=\"Beilharz\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KhvHDwAAQBAJ|last=Beilharz|first=Edwin A.|last2=DeMers|first2=Donald O. Jr.|title=KBAY/KEEN: Broadcasting to serve their community|work=San Jose: California's First City|place=Tulsa, Oklahoma|publisher=Continental Heritage Press|year=1980|isbn=0932986137|via=Google Books}}</ref> Programming included news from the [[United Press International#History|United Press]],<ref name=\"1948 yearbook\"/> Saturday night [[barn dance|barn dances]],<ref>{{citation|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=11023&context=spartandaily|title='540' boys to play for barn dance|work=Spartan Daily|page=2|publisher=San Jose State College|date=January 16, 1948|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> and [[Santa Clara Broncos baseball|University of Santa Clara baseball]] games.<ref>{{citation|url=https://content.scu.edu/digital/collection/broncoseg/id/6102/rec/1|title=The Bull Pen|last=Winklebleck|first=Sam H.|work=The Santa Clara|publisher=University of Santa Clara|date=March 9, 1949|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>  By 1954, KEEN had a [[country music|country and western music]] format featuring hosts like [[Red Murrell]], [[Cal Smith]], and [[Foy Willing]].<ref name=\"Beilharz\"/><ref name=\"Bay Area Radio Museum\"/><ref name=\"Singleton\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5JaoGKu3OOUC&pg=PA113|title=Centerville, Fremont|last=Singleton|first=Jill M.|last2=Holmes|first2=Philip|page=113|place=Charleston, South Carolina|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2011|isbn=9780738581774|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/cal-smith-mn0000647518/biography|title=Cal Smith|last=Manheim|first=James|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> KEEN began broadcasting [[San Jose State Spartans football|San Jose State College football]] games in 1956.<ref>{{citation|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=12399&context=spartandaily|title=Bronzan, Team In Hawaii Finale|work=Spartan Daily|publisher=San Jose State College|volume=44|issue=44|page=3|date=November 30, 1956}}</ref> \n\nOn September 19, 1957, KEEN was granted a license for a new transmitter with a stronger daytime broadcasting power of 5,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> By 1960, KEEN added [[San Jose State Spartans men's basketball|San Jose State basketball]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=4099&context=spartandaily|title=KEEN airs tilts|work=Spartan Daily|date=December 2, 1960|volume=48|issue=45|page=4|publisher=San Jose State College|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The following year, KEEN began broadcasting select [[Santa Clara Broncos men's basketball|Santa Clara basketball]] games.<ref>{{citation|url=https://content.scu.edu/digital/collection/broncoseg/id/28961|title=Holiday Games Feature WCAC Tourney at SF|work=The Santa Clara|date=December 14, 1961|page=7|publisher=University of Santa Clara|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 1963, United Broadcasting launched a sister station that played [[pop standards]], [[KBRG|KEEN-FM]], on 100.3 MHz.<ref name=\"Beilharz\"/><ref name=\"Billboard 1966\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5SgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26|title=Stations by format|work=Billboard|date=March 26, 1966|volume=78|issue=13|page=26}}</ref> KEEN began broadcasting at its current power level of 5,000 watts at both day and night on August 26, 1964.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> By 1966, KEEN began playing selections from comedy records in addition to country music.<ref name=\"Billboard 1966\"/> The two KEEN stations no longer shared call letters in 1967, as KEEN-FM became KBAY.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1967/1967-03-13-BC.pdf|title=Call letter actions|work=Broadcasting|page=84|volume=72|issue=11|date=March 13, 1967|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> KEEN expanded its live sports play-by-play to include [[Santa Clara Broncos football|Santa Clara football]] in 1969.<ref>{{citation|last=Merolla|first=Vic|title=Broncs Face Long Beach State Tough Offense and Defense|url=https://content.scu.edu/digital/collection/broncoseg/id/8986/rec/14|work=The Santa Clara|publisher=University of Santa Clara|date=October 24, 1969|accessdate=March 27, 2020|page=1}}</ref>\n\nThe 1970s marked several changes for KEEN. Murrell left KEEN in 1970 after 16 years.<ref name=\"Singleton\"/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g6kwDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140|title=Workin' Man Blues: Country Music in California|last=Haslam|first=Gerald W.|last2=Russell|first2=Alexandra Haslam|last3=Chon|first3=Richard|place=Berkeley, California|publisher=University of California Press|year=1999|isbn=9780520275058|page=140|via=Google Books}}</ref> After the 1970\u201371 season, KEEN phased out its live college sports coverage in favor of pro sports. Santa Clara sports broadcasts moved to Los Altos FM station [[KJLV (FM)|KPEN]],<ref>{{citation|url=https://content.scu.edu/digital/collection/broncoseg/id/6469|title=Defense Prepares For Rebel Attack|last=Chipp|first=Steve|work=The Santa Clara|publisher=University of Santa Clara|date=October 8, 1971|accessdate=March 27, 2020|page=4}}</ref> and San Jose State broadcasts also moved to FM on Santa Clara's [[KVVN|KREP]].<ref>{{citation|last=Osterman|first=Tim|title=Spartans try Long Beach in crucial PCAA encounter|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=5546&context=spartandaily|work=Spartan Daily|publisher=San Jose State College|date=October 8, 1971|page=7|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> From 1971 to 1975, KEEN was the flagship station of the [[Oakland Athletics Radio Network|Oakland A's Radio Network]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Oakland Athletics Baseball On The Radio |url=https://bayarearadio.org/sports-index/athletics |website=Bay Area Radio Museum |date=13 August 2014}}</ref> KEEN also broadcast [[California Golden Seals]] games until the team moved out of the Bay Area in 1976.<ref>{{cite web |title=California Golden Seals Radio Coverage Map (1974-75) |url=https://bayarearadio.org/keen/seals_coverage-map |website=Bay Area Radio Museum |date=9 August 2014}}</ref> After over 25 years operating out of Hotel De Anza, United Broadcasting moved the KEEN and KBAY to [[West San Jose]] in 1974, on the top floor of the Golden Pacific Building at Winchester Boulevard.<ref name=\"Beilharz\"/> \n\nBy 1976, KEEN began playing newer country singles on weekday afternoons while focusing on [[classic country]] for the rest of the day.<ref>{{citation|url=https://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=6054&context=spartandaily|title=Radio stations offer variety|last=Burns|first=Robert|date=March 9, 1976|page=5|work=Spartan Daily|publisher=San Jose State University|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Following a request filed in 1979, the FCC approved the relocation of KEEN's studios to [[Campbell, California|Campbell]] in 1982.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=37689 FCC Application Search Details:   BML-19820104AH] (click \"Public Notice Comment\")</ref>\n\nBy January 1992, KEEN faced declining ratings and advertising revenue due to competition from FM stations, including new FM country station [[KRTY]].<ref name=\"gets the shaft\"/><ref name=\"Billboard 1995\"/> These factors led United Broadcasting to announce that KEEN would be a simulcast of easy listening FM sister station KBAY.<ref name=\"gets the shaft\">{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF5058366689603&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=KEEN's country gets the shaft|last=Weimers|first=Leigh|work=San Jose Mercury News|page=1D|date=January 22, 1992|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref> However, following much feedback from listeners and advertisers, United Broadcasting reversed this decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF505838EFCDCE0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=KEEN is back in the saddle again|last=Weimers|first=Leigh|date=January 31, 1992|page=1D|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref> However, beginning April 1 that year, KEEN cut its on-air staff to three hosts during daytime hours and broadcast [[broadcast syndication|syndicated]] music by satellite in other time slots.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF5058581FC6AA3&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=Place your bets: Do casinos help economy or not?|last=Weimers|first=Leigh|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=March 27, 1992|page=1E|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref> KEEN went [[dark (broadcasting)|off the air]] on January 1, 1993, after losing its transmitter lease a month earlier as the city of San Jose planned to build nearly 250 houses in the area.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weimers|first=Leigh|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF5058E553726FB&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=Country fans do a two-step with luck, good and bad|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=December 18, 1992|page=1D|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref><ref name=\"1976 transmitter\">{{cite web|url=https://bayarearadio.org/keen/keen_xmtr-bldg_1976|title=KEEN radio, San Jose, Transmitter Site circa 1976|publisher=Bay Area Radio Museum|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===As KKSJ (1993\u20131998)===\nOn October 11, 1993, KEEN became KKSJ.<ref name=\"FCC data\"/><ref name=\"Billboard 1995\">{{citation|last=Boehlert|first=Eric|title=Revived Station Trades Country Tunes for Sinatra|work=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7AsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA87&dq=KEEN+%22San+jose%22+country&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiF086x4bvoAhWBbc0KHQ9ECHgQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=KEEN%20%22San%20jose%22%20country&f=false|date=March 25, 1995|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Google Books}}</ref> After United Broadcasting made an arrangement for KKSJ to share the transmitter site near [[U.S. Highway 101]], a [[Union Pacific Railroad]] overpass, and an [[Eggo]] factory with fellow San Jose AM station [[KSJX]], KKSJ resumed broadcasting in 1994 with the brand \"Magic 1370\" and a [[pop standards]] format inspired by the former \"Magic 61\" brand of San Francisco's [[KEAR (AM)|KFRC]].<ref name=\"1976 transmitter\"/><ref name=\"Billboard 1995\"/> \"Magic 1370\" had a playlist from a 1,700-song library, including nearly 175 [[Frank Sinatra]] songs and others by artists including [[Ella Fitzgerald]] and [[Tony Bennett]].<ref name=\"Billboard 1995\"/> [[Jim Lange]], former KFRC DJ and host of ''[[The Dating Game]]'', joined KKSJ as a weekend host.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF7567C8A4A0E23&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=Jim Lange has a date in San Jose|last=Kava|first=Brad|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=August 12, 1994|page=Eye 20|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref>\n\nKKSJ rose from being unranked in the winter 1994 [[Arbitron]] Bay Area ratings to a 2.9 share by the fall of 1994.<ref name=\"Billboard 1995\"/> Lange left KKSJ in 1996.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB72068F39163A2&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=KABL tunes into big-band format and adds big-name DJs|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=January 28, 1997|last=Kava|first=Brad|page=10E|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1997, United Broadcasting sold KKSJ and KBAY to American Radio Systems for a combined $31.2 million.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1997/BC-1997-02-03.pdf|title=Station & Cable Trading|work=Broadcasting & Cable|volume=127|issue=5|date=February 3, 1997|page=32|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> American Radio subsequently laid off two hosts and dropped the locally programmed music for the syndicated [[Timeless (radio network)|Stardust]] music service.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF8576E14A8BDEF&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|last=Kava|first=Brad|title=Pondering local moves by corporate radio|work=San Jose Mercury News|page=Eye 20|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref> American Radio sold KKSJ to Douglas Broadcasting for $3.2 million in June 1997 and changed it to an Asian ethnic format with [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] and [[Cantonese]] programming.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Business-Report/Radio-Business-Report/1997/RBR-1997-06-30.pdf|title=Transaction Digest|work=Radio Business Report|date=June 30, 1997|volume=14|issue=26|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ORGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EF857741739CFB5&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0|title=KKSJ changes format - Sorkin wants new home|last=Kava|first=Brad|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=June 6, 1997|page=Eye 26|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=Newsbank}}</ref>\n\n===As KZSF (1998\u2013present)===\nOn January 20, 1998, the station changed its call sign to the current KZSF and entered a [[local marketing agreement]] to be a San Francisco Bay Area affiliate of [[Bustos Media|Amador Bustos]]'s Z-Spanish Radio Network of [[regional Mexican]] music stations, alongside sister station [[KREV (FM)|KZSF-FM]] in Alameda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=68841&Callsign=KZSF |title=KZSF Call Sign History |work=Federal Communications Commission }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1998-01.pdf|title=Format Changes & Updates|work=The M Street Journal|date=January 14, 1998|volume=15|issue=2|page=1|accessdate=March 27, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980703020907/http://www.zspanish.com/p0000022.htm|archivedate=July 3, 1998|url=http://zspanish.com/p0000022.htm|title=Radio Stations|publisher=Z-Spanish Radio Network|accessdate=March 27, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bustos bought KZSF and five other stations from Douglas Broadcasting for $27 million in June 1998.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1999/BC-1999-02-15.pdf|title=Dealing for Dollars: TV and radio top sellers in 1998|work=Broadcasting & Cable|page=55|date=February 15, 1999|volume=129|issue=7|accessdate=March 28, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1998/BC-1998-07-06.pdf|title=Z-Spanish merging with Achievement Radio Holdings|work=Broadcasting & Cable|page=48|volume=128|issue=28|date=July 6, 1998|accessdate=March 28, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> For the first time since 1982 as KEEN, KZSF operated in San Jose, with a new location at Wooster Avenue near [[North San Jose]].<reF>{{cite book|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1999/D-Radio-All-BC-YB-1999..pdf|title=Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 1999|page=D-61|place=New Providence, New Jersey|publisher=R.R. Bowker|year=1999|isbn=0835241114|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref> In June 2001, Carlos Duharte bought KZSF for $5 million and relocated the station to Tisch Way in West San Jose.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Business-Report/Radio-Business-Report/2001/RBR-2001-07-02.pdf|title=Transaction Digest|last=Seyler|first=Dave|last2=Messmer|first2=Dave|work=Radio Business Report|date=July 2, 2001|page=14|volume=18|issue=27|accessdate=March 28, 2020|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2001/D-Radio-All-BC-YB-2001.pdf|title=Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 2001|page=D-62|place=New Providence, New Jersey|publisher=Bowker|year=2001|isbn=0835243869|via=AmericanRadioHistory.com}}</ref>\n\nWith its 1998 change to regional Mexican, KZSF added Spanish-language broadcasts of local sports teams, the [[San Francisco Giants]] baseball team and [[San Jose Earthquakes|San Jose Clash (later Earthquakes]] soccer team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Silent-treatment-for-fans-3054689.php|title=Silent treatment for fans|last=Smith|first=Michelle|work=San Francisco Examiner|date=July 8, 2000|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/19981207002003/http://www.clash.com/schedule/index.html</ref> However, the number of Giants games on the station declined from 81 home games in 1999 and 2000 to 40 in 2001 due to the Giants' inability to find advertisers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/article/Missing-in-translation-Spanish-baseball-2566011.php|title=Missing in translation / Spanish baseball broadcasts a tough sell in Bay Area|last=Ortiz|first=Jorge L.|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=July 10, 2003|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> After a hiatus, KZSF resumed Spanish broadcasts of Earthquakes games in 2004 and 2005 before resuming the broadcasts long term beginning in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/post/2010/03/24/english-and-spanish-broadcasts-2010|title=English and Spanish Broadcasts in 2010|publisher=San Jose Earthquakes|date=March 24, 2010|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/post/2013/02/12/kliv-kzsf-return-earthquakes-broadcast-partners|title=KLIV, KZSF return as Earthquakes broadcast partners|publisher=San Jose Earthquakes|date=February 12, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Earthquakes 2018\"/>\n\nUntil April 2002, KZSF was branded \"1370 AM La Z.\"<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20020422095151/http://www.1370am.com/</ref> In May 2002, KZSF changed its branding to \"La Kaliente.\"<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20020525093626/http://www.1370am.com:80/</ref>\n\nFrom 2004 to 2005, KZSF broadcast [[Oakland Raiders]] games in Spanish, before those broadcasts moved to [[KLOK]] in 2006.<ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20041211095651/http://raidersenespanol.com/multimedia/radio.jsp</ref><ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20060908085430/http://www.raidersenespanol.com/multimedia/radio.jsp</ref> KZSF rejoined the Oakland A's Radio Network in 2005, broadcasting 48 games in Spanish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/shea/article/A-S-NOTEBOOK-Team-sale-won-t-be-delayed-by-2723093.php|title=A'S NOTEBOOK / Team sale won't be delayed by House steroid hearings|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=March 16, 2005|accessdate=March 29, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050419161608/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2005/03/16/SPGGEBQ3MO1.DTL|archivedate=April 19, 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> KZSF resumed broadcasting Raiders games in Spanish from 2009 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raiders.com/news/raiders-team-up-with-la-kaliente-710861|title= Raiders Team Up with La Kaliente |publisher=Oakland Raiders|date=July 28, 2009|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raiders.com/news/raiders-se-enfocan-en-delfines-3078868|title= Raiders Se Enfocan En Delfines |publisher=Oakland Raiders|date=November 23, 2010|accessdate=March 29, 2020|language=Spanish}}</reF>\n\n==Programming==\nOn weekdays, KZSF broadcasts a variety of Mexican music, including a nightly program dedicated to [[corrido|corridos]] and [[ranchera]], along with Spanish-language public affairs, advice, and sports talk shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lakaliente1370am.com/horario/|title=Programacion|publisher=La Kaliente 1370 AM|accessdate=March 29, 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> Celina Rodriguez, a former news anchor for local TV stations [[KDTV]] and [[KSTS]], has hosted a talk show on KZSF since 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2006/10/02/popular-anchor-moving-to-radio/|title=Popular anchor moving to radio|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=October 2, 2006|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ktvu.com/news/spanish-radio-host-using-airwaves-to-inform-how-to-help-those-suffering-from-mexico-city-quake|title=Spanish radio host using airwaves to inform how to help those suffering from Mexico City quake|publisher=KTVU|accessdate=March 29, 2020|date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> Additionally, KZSF carries Spanish-language broadcasts of [[San Jose Earthquakes]] games.<ref name=\"Earthquakes 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sjearthquakes.com/post/2018/02/28/news-knbr-1050-1370-kzsf-continue-home-quakes-radio-broadcasts|title=NEWS: KNBR 1050, 1370 KZSF to Continue as Home for Quakes Radio Broadcasts|publisher=San Jose Earthquakes|date=February 28, 2018|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|KZSF}}\n\n{{San Jose Radio}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in California|ZSF]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in the San Francisco Bay Area|ZSF]]\n[[Category:Regional Mexican radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1947]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language radio stations in California|ZSF]]\n[[Category:1947 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Media in San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:California Golden Seals broadcasters]]\n[[Category:San Jose State Spartans football broadcasters]]\n[[Category:San Jose State Spartans men's basketball]]\n[[Category:Santa Clara Broncos football]]\n[[Category:Santa Clara Broncos men's basketball]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Giants broadcasters]]\n[[Category:San Jose Earthquakes broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders broadcasters]]\n", "name_user": "Arbor to SJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "DisambiguateKLOKtoKLOK (AM)usingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KZSF"}
{"title_page": "Antonio Alcal\u00e1 Venceslada", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish writer, poet}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n'''Antonio Alcal\u00e1 Venceslada''' (1883\u20131955) was a [[Spaniards|Spanish]] writer and scholar of [[Andalusia]]. He studied variously in M\u00e1laga, Jaen, Granada and Sevilla. As an archivist/librarian, he worked in Compostela, C\u00e1diz, Huelva and Ja\u00e9n. He also taught at the Instituto Virgen del Carmen in Ja\u00e9n.\n\nAlcal\u00e1 Venceslada was a renowned authority on [[Andalusia]]n popular culture. He wrote many books, the most important of which, a reference work called ''Vocabulario Andaluz'', was published in 1934. The author was awarded the sum of 10,000 pesetas by the [[Real Academia Espa\u00f1ola de la Lengua]] as a result. The book has been reprinted many times since. Other works include ''De la solera fina'' (Ja\u00e9n, 1925) and ''La flor de la canela'' (And\u00fajar, 1946). He was also a noted poet. According to [[Alfonso de Urquijo]], Alcal\u00e1 Venceslada was \"el poeta montero de Espa\u00f1a\". A street and a college in [[Ja\u00e9n, Spain|Jaen]] are named after him, likewise a small street in [[And\u00fajar]].<ref>[http://www.jaen.es/sociedad/jiennenses-destacados/literatura-humanidades/antonio-alcala-venceslada.html Bio]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alcala Vencelada, Antonio}}\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Spain-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish writer, poet}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n'''Antonio Alcal\u00e1 Venceslada''' (1883\u20131955) was a [[Spaniards|Spanish]] writer and scholar of [[Andalusia]]. He studied variously in M\u00e1laga, Jaen, Granada and Sevilla. As an archivist/librarian, he worked in Compostela, C\u00e1diz, Huelva and Ja\u00e9n. He also taught at the Instituto Virgen del Carmen in Ja\u00e9n.\n\nAlcal\u00e1 Venceslada was a renowned authority on [[Andalusia]]n popular culture. He wrote many books, the most important of which, a reference work called ''Vocabulario Andaluz'', was published in 1934. The author was awarded the sum of 10,000 pesetas by the [[Real Academia Espa\u00f1ola de la Lengua]] as a result. The book has been reprinted many times since. Other works include ''De la solera fina'' (Ja\u00e9n, 1925) and ''La flor de la canela'' (And\u00fajar, 1946). He was also a noted poet. According to [[Alfonso de Urquijo]], Alcal\u00e1 Venceslada was \"el poeta montero de Espa\u00f1a\". A street and a college in [[Ja\u00e9n, Spain|Jaen]] are named after him, likewise a small street in [[And\u00fajar]].<ref>[http://www.jaen.es/sociedad/jiennenses-destacados/literatura-humanidades/antonio-alcala-venceslada.html Bio]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alcala Vencelada, Antonio}}\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Spain-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Alcal%C3%A1_Venceslada"}
{"title_page": "Thame Rangers F.C.", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Thame Rangers\n| image    = ThameRangers.png\n| fullname = Thame Rangers Football Club\n| nickname =\n| founded  =\n| ground   = Thame United FC, [[Thame]]\n| capacity = 2,500<ref name=NLCD>Mike Williams & Tony Williams (2012) ''Non-League Club Directory 2013'', p670 {{ISBN|978-1-869833-77-0}}</ref>\n| chairman =\n| manager  = [[Craig Faulconbridge]]\n| league   = {{English football updater|ThameRan}}\n| season   = {{English football updater|ThameRan2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|ThameRan3}}\n}}\n\n'''Thame Rangers Football Club''' is a [[association football|football]] club originally based in [[Thame]], [[Oxfordshire]], England. They are currently members of the {{English football updater|ThameRan}} and play at Meadow View Park.\n\n==History==\nThe club joined the Senior Section of the Wycombe & District League in 2015, going on to win the league title losing only one league game all season.<ref>[http://www.football.mitoo.co.uk/LeagueTab.cfm?TblName=Matches&DivisionID=19223&LeagueCode=WDFL2015 Senior Section] Football Mitoo</ref> They then joined Division Two of the Spartan South Midlands League, which they also won at the first attempt,<ref name=FCHD>{{fchd|id=THAMERAN|name=Thame Rangers}}</ref> resulting in promotion. They were also transferred to the [[Hellenic Football League|Hellenic League]], becoming members of Division One East.\n\n==Honours==\n*'''Spartan South Midlands League'''\n**Division Two champions 2016\u201317\n*'''Wycombe & District League'''\n**Senior Division champions 2015\u201316\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hellenic League}}\n{{coord|51|45|21.0384|N|0|58|33.9342|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Hellenic Football League]]\n[[Category:Thame]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Thame Rangers\n| image    = ThameRangers.png\n| fullname = Thame Rangers Football Club\n| nickname =\n| founded  =\n| ground   = Meadow View Park, [[Thame]]\n| capacity = 2,500<ref name=NLCD>Mike Williams & Tony Williams (2012) ''Non-League Club Directory 2013'', p670 {{ISBN|978-1-869833-77-0}}</ref>\n| chairman =\n| manager  = [[Craig Faulconbridge]]\n| league   = {{English football updater|ThameRan}}\n| season   = {{English football updater|ThameRan2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|ThameRan3}}\n}}\n\n'''Thame Rangers Football Club''' is a [[association football|football]] club originally based in [[Thame]], [[Oxfordshire]], England. They are currently members of the {{English football updater|ThameRan}} and play at Meadow View Park.\n\n==History==\nThe club joined the Senior Section of the Wycombe & District League in 2015, going on to win the league title losing only one league game all season.<ref>[http://www.football.mitoo.co.uk/LeagueTab.cfm?TblName=Matches&DivisionID=19223&LeagueCode=WDFL2015 Senior Section] Football Mitoo</ref> They then joined Division Two of the Spartan South Midlands League, which they also won at the first attempt,<ref name=FCHD>{{fchd|id=THAMERAN|name=Thame Rangers}}</ref> resulting in promotion. They were also transferred to the [[Hellenic Football League|Hellenic League]], becoming members of Division One East.\n\n==Honours==\n*'''Spartan South Midlands League'''\n**Division Two champions 2016\u201317\n*'''Wycombe & District League'''\n**Senior Division champions 2015\u201316\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hellenic League}}\n{{coord|51|45|21.0384|N|0|58|33.9342|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Hellenic Football League]]\n[[Category:Thame]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c7:e12:2701:89e5:9f1c:27ec:344", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thame_Rangers_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Pan (moon)", "text_new": "{{short description|Moon of Saturn}}\n{{about||the moon of Jupiter formerly known by this name|Carme (moon)|other uses|Pan (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox planet\n| name            = Pan\n| image           = PIA21436.jpg\n| caption         = I LOVE HOT PIZZA ROLLS!\n\n.{{efn|This photo of Pan was acquired by the ''[[Cassini-Huygens|Cassini]]'' spacecraft's narrow-angle Imaging Science Subsystem (ISS) camera on 7 March 2017. This view of the moon's northern hemisphere shows its [[walnut]]-like appearance, with a highly inclined equatorial ridge almost eclipsing the moon's southern hemisphere from view.}}\n| discovered      = July 16, 1990\n| pronounced      = {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u00e6|n}}\n| named_after     = [[Pan (mythology)|\u03a0\u03ac\u03bd]] ''P\u0101n<!--the 'a' is long in Greek, as reflected in the Latin, even if not written in Greek-->''\n| mpc_name        = Saturn XVIII\n| alt_names       = S/1981 S 13\n| adjectives      = Pandean {{IPAc-en|p|\u00e6|n|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|\u0259|n}}<ref>{{OED|Pandean}}</ref>\n| discoverer      = [[Mark R. Showalter|M. R. Showalter]]\n| period          = {{val|0.575050718|u=days}} ({{val|13.801217|u=hours}})\n| dimensions      = 34.4&thinsp;\u00d7&thinsp;31.4&thinsp;\u00d7&thinsp;20.8 km\n| mean_radius     = {{val|14.1|1.3|u=km}}<ref name=Thomas2010/>\n| density         = {{val|0.42|0.15|u=g/cm\u00b3}}<ref name=Thomas2010/>\n| escape_velocity = \u2248&thinsp;0.006 km/s\n| orbit_ref       = <ref name=\"Jacobson2008\">{{cite journal | author= Jacobson, R. A. | display-authors= etal| title= Revised orbits of Saturn's small inner satellites| journal=[[Astronomical Journal]]| date= 2008| volume= 135 | issue= 1| pages= 261\u2013263| bibcode=2008AJ....135..261J | doi= 10.1088/0004-6256/135/1/261| citeseerx= 10.1.1.653.3917}}</ref>\n| semimajor       = {{val|133584.0|0.1|u=km}}\n| eccentricity    = {{val|0.0000144|0.0000054}}\n| inclination     = {{val|0.0001|0.0004|u=\u00b0}}\n| satellite_of    = [[Saturn]]\n| group           = [[Shepherd moon]] of the [[Encke Gap]]\n| mass            = {{val|4.95|0.75|e=15|u=kg}}<ref name=Thomas2010>{{cite journal| doi = 10.1016/j.icarus.2010.01.025| last1 = Thomas| first1 = P. C.| date = July 2010| title = Sizes, shapes, and derived properties of the saturnian satellites after the Cassini nominal mission| journal = Icarus| volume = 208| issue = 1| pages = 395\u2013401| pmid = | pmc = | url = http://www.ciclops.org/media/sp/2011/6794_16344_0.pdf| bibcode = 2010Icar..208..395T| ref = harv}}</ref>\n| surface_grav    = 0.0001\u20130.0018 [[Acceleration|m/s<sup>2</sup>]]\n| rotation        = [[synchronous rotation|synchronous]]\n| axial_tilt      = zero\n| albedo          = 0.5\n| single_temperature = \u2248&thinsp;78 K\n}}\n\n'''Pan''' is the innermost<ref name=\"Moons of Saturn\">{{cite web |url=https://solarsystem.nasa.gov/planets/saturn/moons |title=Saturn - Moons |work=NASA |accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> named [[Natural satellite|moon]] of [[Saturn]]. It is a small, [[walnut]]-shaped moon approximately 35 [[kilometre]]s across and 23&nbsp;km wide that orbits within the [[Encke Gap]] in Saturn's [[A Ring]]. Pan is a [[Shepherd moon|ring shepherd]] and is responsible for keeping the Encke Gap free of ring particles. It is sometimes described as having the appearance of a [[ravioli]].<ref name=\"Ravioli\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/nasa-saturn-pan-cassini-ravioli-moon/ |title=Saturn's Tiny Moon Pan Looks Like a Ravioli |work=CNET |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was discovered by [[Mark R. Showalter]] in 1990 from analysis of old ''Voyager 2'' probe photos and received the provisional designation '''{{nowrap|S/1981 S 13}}''' because the discovery images dated back to 1981.<ref name=\"iauc5052\">[http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/iauc/05000/05052.html IAUC 5052: ''Saturn''] July 16, 1990 (discovery)</ref>\n\n==Prediction and discovery==\nThe existence of a moon in the Encke Gap was first predicted by Jeffrey N. Cuzzi and Jeffrey D. Scargle in 1985, based on wavy edges of the gap which indicated a gravitational disturbance.<ref>Cuzzi, J. N.; and Scargle, J. D.; [http://adsabs.harvard.edu//full/seri/ApJ../0292//0000276.000.html ''Wavy Edges Suggest Moonlet in Encke's Gap''], Astrophysical Journal, Vol. 292 (May 1, 1985), pp. 276\u2013290</ref> In 1986 Showalter ''et al.'' inferred its orbit and mass by modeling its gravitational wake. They arrived at a very precise prediction of 133,603 \u00b1 10&nbsp;km for the semi-major axis and a mass of 5&ndash;10{{e|&minus;12}} Saturn masses, and inferred that there was only a single moon within the Encke gap.<ref name=\"Showalter1986\">{{cite journal | author= Showalter, M. R. | display-authors= etal| title= Satellite \"wakes\" and the orbit of the Encke Gap moonlet| journal= Icarus| date= 1986| volume= 66 | issue= 2| pages= 297\u2013323| bibcode= 1986Icar...66..297S | doi = 10.1016/0019-1035(86)90160-0| url= https://zenodo.org/record/1253894}}</ref> The actual semi-major axis differs by 19&nbsp;km and the actual mass is 8.6{{e|&minus;12}} of Saturn's.\n\nThe moon was later found within 1\u00b0 of the predicted position. The search was undertaken by considering all ''[[Voyager 2]]'' images and using a computer calculation to predict whether the moon would be visible under sufficiently favorable conditions in each one. Every qualifying Voyager 2 image with resolution better than ~50&nbsp;km/pixel shows Pan clearly. In all, it appears in eleven ''Voyager 2'' images.<ref name=\"Showalter1990\">{{cite journal | author=Showalter, M. R.| title= Visual Detection of 1981 S 13, the Encke Gap Moonlet| journal=  Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society| date= 1990| volume= 22| pages= 1031| url= http://adsabs.harvard.edu//full/seri/BAAS./0022//0001040.000.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Showalter1991\">{{cite journal | author= Showalter, M. R.| title= Visual detection of 1981 S 13, Saturn's eighteenth satellite, and its role in the Encke gap| journal= Nature| date= 1991| volume= 351 | issue= 6329| pages= 709\u2013713| doi=  10.1038/351709a0|bibcode = 1991Natur.351..709S }}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe moon was named on 16 September 1991,<ref>[http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/iauc/05300/05347.html IAUC 5347: ''Satellites of Saturn and Neptune''] 1991 September 16 (naming the moon)</ref> after the mythological [[Pan (mythology)|Pan]], who was (among other things) the god of shepherds.  This is a reference to Pan's role as a [[shepherd moon]].  It is also designated '''{{nowrap|Saturn XVIII}}'''.<ref name=\"Gazetteer\">{{cite web|title = Planet and Satellite Names and Discoverers|work = Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature|publisher = USGS Astrogeology|date = July 21, 2006|url = http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/append7.html|accessdate = 2006-08-07 }}</ref>\n\n==Orbit==\nThe [[eccentricity (orbit)|eccentricity]] of Pan's orbit causes its distance from Saturn to vary by ~4&nbsp;km.  Its [[inclination]], which would cause it to move up and down, is not distinguishable from zero with present data.  The [[Encke Gap]], within which Pan orbits, is about 325&nbsp;km wide.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Pan (moon) edge-on.jpg|thumb|right|Pan, photographed by ''[[Cassini\u2013Huygens|Cassini]]'' on March 7, 2017. The thin [[equatorial ridge]] is clearly visible.]]\n''[[Cassini-Huygens|Cassini]]'' scientists have described Pan as \"[[walnut]]-shaped\"<ref>[http://photojournal.jpl.nasa.gov/catalog/PIA08320 \"PIA08320: Cruising with Pan\"], ''[[Planetary Photojournal]]''.</ref> owing to the [[equatorial ridge]], similar to that on [[Atlas (moon)|Atlas]], that is visible in images. The ridge is due to ring material that Pan has swept up from the Encke gap. It has also been referred to by journalists as a space [[empanada]], a form of stuffed bread or pastry, as well as a [[Ravioli|ravioli]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chang|first1=Kenneth|title=Pan, Moon of Saturn, Looks Like a Cosmic Ravioli (or Maybe a Walnut)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/10/science/nasa-cassini-saturn-moon-pan.html?_r=0|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|date=10 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Space empanada\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/03/space-empanada-frozen-ridge-around-saturn-s-moon-pan-collected-planet-s-rings |title= Stunning close-up of Saturn's moon, Pan, reveals a space empanada |last=Perkins |first=Sid |website=Science |date=2017-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Pandean ringlet==\nThe Encke Gap contains a ringlet that is coincident with Pan's orbit, indicating that Pan maintains the particles in [[horseshoe orbit]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hedman|first1=M.M.|last2=Burns|first2=J.A.|last3=Hamilton|first3=D.P.|last4=Showalter|first4=M.R.|title=Of horseshoes and heliotropes: Dynamics of dust in the Encke Gap|journal=Icarus|date=2013|volume=223|issue=1|pages=252\u2013276|doi=10.1016/j.icarus.2012.11.036|arxiv=1211.4762|bibcode=2013Icar..223..252H}}</ref> A second ringlet is periodically disrupted by Pan, similarly to how the [[F Ring]] is disturbed by [[Prometheus (moon)|Prometheus]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Porco|first1=C.C.|last2=Baker|first2=E.|last3=Barbara|first3=John|last4=Beurle|first4=K.|last5=Brahic|first5=A.|last6=Burns|first6=J.A.|last7=Charnoz|first7=S.|last8=Cooper|first8=N.|last9=Dawson|first9=Douglas|last10=Delgenio|first10=Anthony|last11=Denk|first11=T.|last12=Dones|first12=Luke|last13=Dyudina|first13=Ulyana|last14=Evans|first14=M.W.|last15=Giese|first15=B.|last16=Grazier|first16=Kim|last17=Helfenstein|first17=Paul|last18=Ingersoll|first18=A.P.|last19=Jacobson|first19=R.A.|last20=West|first20=Robert|title=Cassini Imaging Science: Initial Results on Saturn's Rings and Small Satellites|journal=Science|date=2005|issue=307|pages=1226\u20131236|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:PIA06534 Encke Division.jpg|Closeup of the Encke Gap, showing the central ringlet that is coincident with Pan's orbit.\nFile:Pans highway 3-05-07.jpg|''Cassini'' image showing Pan orbiting in the Encke Gap.\nFile:Pan side view.jpg|Equatorial view of Pan from ''Cassini'', with the rings of Saturn surrounding the moon.\nFile:Pan Rev09.2x.jpg|Pan in the center of the image, occupying the Encke Gap in Saturn's rings. Its walnut-like shape is clearly visible.\nFile:PIA21436 - Pan, 3 versions.jpg|Stretched (4x) images, processed in various ways.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n;Citations\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Pan (moon)}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Pan_(moon).ogg|2010-01-16}}\n* [http://solarsystem.nasa.gov/planets/profile.cfm?Object=Sat_Pan Pan Profile] by [http://solarsystem.nasa.gov NASA's Solar System Exploration]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060927042138/http://www.planetary.org/explore/topics/our_solar_system/saturn/pan.html The Planetary Society: Pan]\n\n{{Moons of Saturn|state=uncollapsed}}\n{{Saturn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pan (Moon)}}\n[[Category:Moons of Saturn]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1990|19900716]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Moon of Saturn}}\n{{about||the moon of Jupiter formerly known by this name|Carme (moon)|other uses|Pan (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox planet\n| name            = Pan\n| image           = PIA21436.jpg\n| caption         = View of Pan by ''Cassini'' in 2017.{{efn|This photo of Pan was acquired by the ''[[Cassini-Huygens|Cassini]]'' spacecraft's narrow-angle Imaging Science Subsystem (ISS) camera on 7 March 2017. This view of the moon's northern hemisphere shows its [[walnut]]-like appearance, with a highly inclined equatorial ridge almost eclipsing the moon's southern hemisphere from view.}}\n| discovered      = July 16, 1990\n| pronounced      = {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u00e6|n}}\n| named_after     = [[Pan (mythology)|\u03a0\u03ac\u03bd]] ''P\u0101n<!--the 'a' is long in Greek, as reflected in the Latin, even if not written in Greek-->''\n| mpc_name        = Saturn XVIII\n| alt_names       = S/1981 S 13\n| adjectives      = Pandean {{IPAc-en|p|\u00e6|n|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|\u0259|n}}<ref>{{OED|Pandean}}</ref>\n| discoverer      = [[Mark R. Showalter|M. R. Showalter]]\n| period          = {{val|0.575050718|u=days}} ({{val|13.801217|u=hours}})\n| dimensions      = 34.4&thinsp;\u00d7&thinsp;31.4&thinsp;\u00d7&thinsp;20.8 km\n| mean_radius     = {{val|14.1|1.3|u=km}}<ref name=Thomas2010/>\n| density         = {{val|0.42|0.15|u=g/cm\u00b3}}<ref name=Thomas2010/>\n| escape_velocity = \u2248&thinsp;0.006 km/s\n| orbit_ref       = <ref name=\"Jacobson2008\">{{cite journal | author= Jacobson, R. A. | display-authors= etal| title= Revised orbits of Saturn's small inner satellites| journal=[[Astronomical Journal]]| date= 2008| volume= 135 | issue= 1| pages= 261\u2013263| bibcode=2008AJ....135..261J | doi= 10.1088/0004-6256/135/1/261| citeseerx= 10.1.1.653.3917}}</ref>\n| semimajor       = {{val|133584.0|0.1|u=km}}\n| eccentricity    = {{val|0.0000144|0.0000054}}\n| inclination     = {{val|0.0001|0.0004|u=\u00b0}}\n| satellite_of    = [[Saturn]]\n| group           = [[Shepherd moon]] of the [[Encke Gap]]\n| mass            = {{val|4.95|0.75|e=15|u=kg}}<ref name=Thomas2010>{{cite journal| doi = 10.1016/j.icarus.2010.01.025| last1 = Thomas| first1 = P. C.| date = July 2010| title = Sizes, shapes, and derived properties of the saturnian satellites after the Cassini nominal mission| journal = Icarus| volume = 208| issue = 1| pages = 395\u2013401| pmid = | pmc = | url = http://www.ciclops.org/media/sp/2011/6794_16344_0.pdf| bibcode = 2010Icar..208..395T| ref = harv}}</ref>\n| surface_grav    = 0.0001\u20130.0018 [[Acceleration|m/s<sup>2</sup>]]\n| rotation        = [[synchronous rotation|synchronous]]\n| axial_tilt      = zero\n| albedo          = 0.5\n| single_temperature = \u2248&thinsp;78 K\n}}\n\n'''Pan''' is the innermost<ref name=\"Moons of Saturn\">{{cite web |url=https://solarsystem.nasa.gov/planets/saturn/moons |title=Saturn - Moons |work=NASA |accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> named [[Natural satellite|moon]] of [[Saturn]]. It is a small, [[walnut]]-shaped moon approximately 35 [[kilometre]]s across and 23&nbsp;km wide that orbits within the [[Encke Gap]] in Saturn's [[A Ring]]. Pan is a [[Shepherd moon|ring shepherd]] and is responsible for keeping the Encke Gap free of ring particles. It is sometimes described as having the appearance of a [[ravioli]].<ref name=\"Ravioli\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/nasa-saturn-pan-cassini-ravioli-moon/ |title=Saturn's Tiny Moon Pan Looks Like a Ravioli |work=CNET |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was discovered by [[Mark R. Showalter]] in 1990 from analysis of old ''Voyager 2'' probe photos and received the provisional designation '''{{nowrap|S/1981 S 13}}''' because the discovery images dated back to 1981.<ref name=\"iauc5052\">[http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/iauc/05000/05052.html IAUC 5052: ''Saturn''] July 16, 1990 (discovery)</ref>\n\n==Prediction and discovery==\nThe existence of a moon in the Encke Gap was first predicted by Jeffrey N. Cuzzi and Jeffrey D. Scargle in 1985, based on wavy edges of the gap which indicated a gravitational disturbance.<ref>Cuzzi, J. N.; and Scargle, J. D.; [http://adsabs.harvard.edu//full/seri/ApJ../0292//0000276.000.html ''Wavy Edges Suggest Moonlet in Encke's Gap''], Astrophysical Journal, Vol. 292 (May 1, 1985), pp. 276\u2013290</ref> In 1986 Showalter ''et al.'' inferred its orbit and mass by modeling its gravitational wake. They arrived at a very precise prediction of 133,603 \u00b1 10&nbsp;km for the semi-major axis and a mass of 5&ndash;10{{e|&minus;12}} Saturn masses, and inferred that there was only a single moon within the Encke gap.<ref name=\"Showalter1986\">{{cite journal | author= Showalter, M. R. | display-authors= etal| title= Satellite \"wakes\" and the orbit of the Encke Gap moonlet| journal= Icarus| date= 1986| volume= 66 | issue= 2| pages= 297\u2013323| bibcode= 1986Icar...66..297S | doi = 10.1016/0019-1035(86)90160-0| url= https://zenodo.org/record/1253894}}</ref> The actual semi-major axis differs by 19&nbsp;km and the actual mass is 8.6{{e|&minus;12}} of Saturn's.\n\nThe moon was later found within 1\u00b0 of the predicted position. The search was undertaken by considering all ''[[Voyager 2]]'' images and using a computer calculation to predict whether the moon would be visible under sufficiently favorable conditions in each one. Every qualifying Voyager 2 image with resolution better than ~50&nbsp;km/pixel shows Pan clearly. In all, it appears in eleven ''Voyager 2'' images.<ref name=\"Showalter1990\">{{cite journal | author=Showalter, M. R.| title= Visual Detection of 1981 S 13, the Encke Gap Moonlet| journal=  Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society| date= 1990| volume= 22| pages= 1031| url= http://adsabs.harvard.edu//full/seri/BAAS./0022//0001040.000.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Showalter1991\">{{cite journal | author= Showalter, M. R.| title= Visual detection of 1981 S 13, Saturn's eighteenth satellite, and its role in the Encke gap| journal= Nature| date= 1991| volume= 351 | issue= 6329| pages= 709\u2013713| doi=  10.1038/351709a0|bibcode = 1991Natur.351..709S }}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe moon was named on 16 September 1991,<ref>[http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/iauc/05300/05347.html IAUC 5347: ''Satellites of Saturn and Neptune''] 1991 September 16 (naming the moon)</ref> after the mythological [[Pan (mythology)|Pan]], who was (among other things) the god of shepherds.  This is a reference to Pan's role as a [[shepherd moon]].  It is also designated '''{{nowrap|Saturn XVIII}}'''.<ref name=\"Gazetteer\">{{cite web|title = Planet and Satellite Names and Discoverers|work = Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature|publisher = USGS Astrogeology|date = July 21, 2006|url = http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/append7.html|accessdate = 2006-08-07 }}</ref>\n\n==Orbit==\nThe [[eccentricity (orbit)|eccentricity]] of Pan's orbit causes its distance from Saturn to vary by ~4&nbsp;km.  Its [[inclination]], which would cause it to move up and down, is not distinguishable from zero with present data.  The [[Encke Gap]], within which Pan orbits, is about 325&nbsp;km wide.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Pan (moon) edge-on.jpg|thumb|right|Pan, photographed by ''[[Cassini\u2013Huygens|Cassini]]'' on March 7, 2017. The thin [[equatorial ridge]] is clearly visible.]]\n''[[Cassini-Huygens|Cassini]]'' scientists have described Pan as \"[[walnut]]-shaped\"<ref>[http://photojournal.jpl.nasa.gov/catalog/PIA08320 \"PIA08320: Cruising with Pan\"], ''[[Planetary Photojournal]]''.</ref> owing to the [[equatorial ridge]], similar to that on [[Atlas (moon)|Atlas]], that is visible in images. The ridge is due to ring material that Pan has swept up from the Encke gap. It has also been referred to by journalists as a space [[empanada]], a form of stuffed bread or pastry, as well as a [[Ravioli|ravioli]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chang|first1=Kenneth|title=Pan, Moon of Saturn, Looks Like a Cosmic Ravioli (or Maybe a Walnut)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/10/science/nasa-cassini-saturn-moon-pan.html?_r=0|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|date=10 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Space empanada\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/03/space-empanada-frozen-ridge-around-saturn-s-moon-pan-collected-planet-s-rings |title= Stunning close-up of Saturn's moon, Pan, reveals a space empanada |last=Perkins |first=Sid |website=Science |date=2017-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Pandean ringlet==\nThe Encke Gap contains a ringlet that is coincident with Pan's orbit, indicating that Pan maintains the particles in [[horseshoe orbit]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hedman|first1=M.M.|last2=Burns|first2=J.A.|last3=Hamilton|first3=D.P.|last4=Showalter|first4=M.R.|title=Of horseshoes and heliotropes: Dynamics of dust in the Encke Gap|journal=Icarus|date=2013|volume=223|issue=1|pages=252\u2013276|doi=10.1016/j.icarus.2012.11.036|arxiv=1211.4762|bibcode=2013Icar..223..252H}}</ref> A second ringlet is periodically disrupted by Pan, similarly to how the [[F Ring]] is disturbed by [[Prometheus (moon)|Prometheus]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Porco|first1=C.C.|last2=Baker|first2=E.|last3=Barbara|first3=John|last4=Beurle|first4=K.|last5=Brahic|first5=A.|last6=Burns|first6=J.A.|last7=Charnoz|first7=S.|last8=Cooper|first8=N.|last9=Dawson|first9=Douglas|last10=Delgenio|first10=Anthony|last11=Denk|first11=T.|last12=Dones|first12=Luke|last13=Dyudina|first13=Ulyana|last14=Evans|first14=M.W.|last15=Giese|first15=B.|last16=Grazier|first16=Kim|last17=Helfenstein|first17=Paul|last18=Ingersoll|first18=A.P.|last19=Jacobson|first19=R.A.|last20=West|first20=Robert|title=Cassini Imaging Science: Initial Results on Saturn's Rings and Small Satellites|journal=Science|date=2005|issue=307|pages=1226\u20131236|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:PIA06534 Encke Division.jpg|Closeup of the Encke Gap, showing the central ringlet that is coincident with Pan's orbit.\nFile:Pans highway 3-05-07.jpg|''Cassini'' image showing Pan orbiting in the Encke Gap.\nFile:Pan side view.jpg|Equatorial view of Pan from ''Cassini'', with the rings of Saturn surrounding the moon.\nFile:Pan Rev09.2x.jpg|Pan in the center of the image, occupying the Encke Gap in Saturn's rings. Its walnut-like shape is clearly visible.\nFile:PIA21436 - Pan, 3 versions.jpg|Stretched (4x) images, processed in various ways.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n;Citations\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Pan (moon)}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Pan_(moon).ogg|2010-01-16}}\n* [http://solarsystem.nasa.gov/planets/profile.cfm?Object=Sat_Pan Pan Profile] by [http://solarsystem.nasa.gov NASA's Solar System Exploration]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060927042138/http://www.planetary.org/explore/topics/our_solar_system/saturn/pan.html The Planetary Society: Pan]\n\n{{Moons of Saturn|state=uncollapsed}}\n{{Saturn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pan (Moon)}}\n[[Category:Moons of Saturn]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1990|19900716]]\n", "name_user": "90.252.142.214", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pan_(moon)"}
