{"title_page": "DMC DeLorean", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|1980s automobile}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = DMC DeLorean\n| image = Delorean DMC-12 side.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = 1983 DeLorean\n| manufacturer = [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC)<br />[[Bloomfield_Hills,_Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], Michigan, US\n| production = 9,080<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2015/12/19/delorean-book/77623204/|title=DeLoreans still ply the roads -- and memories|url-status=live}}</ref> (disputed)\n| model_years = 1981\u20131983\n| assembly = DeLorean Motor Cars, Ltd. (DMCL) [[Dunmurry]], [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland\n| designer = [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Italdesign]]\n| class = Sports car\n| body_style = 2-door coup\u00e9\n| related = \n| layout = Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| engine = {{convert|2849|cc|L|2|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[V6 PRV engine]] ''ZMJ-159''\n| powerout = {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|207|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| transmission = 5-speed manual<br/>3-speed automatic<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2413|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\">{{Cite book|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946\u20131975|publisher= Krause|isbn=0-87341-027-0|editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first= John A.}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4267|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| width = {{convert|1988|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| height = {{convert|1140|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors closed<br/>{{convert|1962|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors open<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date = 2014| pages = 16}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|1233|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| doors = Gullwing doors\n}}\n\nThe '''DMC DeLorean''' (often referred to simply as the \"'''DeLorean'''\", as it was the only model ever produced by the company) is a sports car manufactured by [[John DeLorean]]'s [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC) for the American market from 1981 to 1983. The car was designed by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] and stood out for its [[gull-wing door]]s and brushed stainless-steel outer body panels, as well as an innovative fiberglass body structure with a steel backbone chassis. It became widely known for its disappointing lack of power and performance, which did not match the expectations created by its looks and price tag, but it became iconic for its appearances as the [[DeLorean time machine|time machine]] in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' media franchise]] after 1985.\n\nThroughout production, the car was generally unchanged, although minor modifications were made to such parts as the hood and wheels. The first production car was completed on January 21, 1981. About 9,000 DeLoreans were made before production halted in late December 1982 shortly after DMC had filed for bankruptcy.\n\n==History==\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 (9979) (cropped).jpg|thumb|A DeLorean with the gull-wing doors closed]]\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 with doors open.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean from the front with the gull-wing doors open]]\nIn October 1976, the first prototype DeLorean was completed by American automotive chief engineer William T. Collins, formerly chief engineer at [[Pontiac]].  Originally, the car was intended to have a centrally-mounted [[Wankel engine|Wankel rotary engine]].  The engine selection was reconsidered when [[Comotor]] production ended, and the favored engine became the [[Ford Cologne V6 engine]].  Eventually the French/Swedish [[fuel injection|fuel-injected]] [[V6 PRV engine]] ([[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]]) was selected.  Also the engine location moved from the mid-engined location in the prototype to a rear-engined installation in the production car.  The [[chassis]] was initially planned to be produced from a new and untested manufacturing technology known as elastic reservoir moulding (ERM), which would lighten the car while presumably lowering its production costs.  This new technology, for which DeLorean had purchased patent rights, was eventually found to be unsuitable.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nThese and other changes to the original concept led to considerable schedule pressures.  The entire car was deemed to require almost complete re-engineering, which was turned over to engineer [[Colin Chapman]], founder of [[Lotus Cars]].  Chapman replaced most of the unproven material and manufacturing techniques with those then employed by Lotus, like the steel backbone chassis.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003| pages = 71\u201375}}</ref>\n\nThe first prototype appeared in October 1976 and was known as the DSV-1, or DeLorean Safety Vehicle.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 23}}</ref> As development continued, the model was referred to as the DSV-12<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 28}}</ref> and later the DMC-12 since DMC was targeting a list price of US$12,000 ({{Inflation|US|12000|1976|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) at release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |title=DeLorean DMC-12 |access-date=February 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204065904/https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |archive-date=February 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html How an immigrant mechanic used $5 million to bring DeLoreans back to the future] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014534/https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html |date=February 4, 2019 }} Zack Guzman. 3:52 PM ET Wed, November 9, 2016</ref>\n\nAfter several delays and cost overruns, production finally began in late 1980. Around this time DMC officially dropped the name DMC-12 on its now US$25,000 ({{Inflation|US|25000|1981|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) car in favor of the model name DeLorean. The DeLorean sports car, as it was described in advertisements, began production in December 1980 with the first production car rolling off the assembly line on January 21, 1981.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lily Rothman |url=http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |title=DeLorean Auto History: What Happened to the Company |publisher=Time |date=January 21, 2016 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423164413/http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |title=Almanac: The DeLorean car |publisher=CBS News |date=January 21, 2018 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515122627/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |archive-date=May 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with James Espey of the new incarnation of the DeLorean Motor Company of [[Texas]], a drawing surfaced showing that the car originally had the potential to be named \"Z Tavio\".  John DeLorean's middle name and his son's first name were both Zachary, while Tavio was his father's name and his son's middle name.  Due to only sporadic documentation, there is little more that is currently known about the Z Tavio name and why it was ultimately rejected in favor of the DeLorean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |title=Interview with James Espy of DMCH |publisher=Myride.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908094456/http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |archive-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nConvincing Hollywood celebrities such as [[Johnny Carson]] and [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] to invest in the firm,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/21/business/21delorean.html | work=The New York Times | title=John Z. DeLorean, Father of Glamour Car, Dies at 80 | first=Danny | last=Hakim | date=March 21, 2005 | accessdate=May 1, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630061902/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/21/business/21delorean.html | archive-date=June 30, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theavanti.com/carson.htm |title=Avanti Celebrity Owners: Johnny Carson |publisher=Theavanti.com |date=May 22, 1992 |accessdate=May 4, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130210603/http://theavanti.com/carson.html|archivedate=November 30, 2010}}</ref> DMC eventually built the DeLorean in a factory in [[Dunmurry]], in [[Northern Ireland]], a neighborhood about {{Convert|10|km|0|abbr=on}} from the city of [[Belfast]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/manufacturing/bright-future-at-old-delorean-plant-in-belfast-1.2397970 |title=Bright future at old DeLorean plant in Belfast |publisher=Irishtimes.com |date=October 20, 2015 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710143132/https://www.irishtimes.com/business/manufacturing/bright-future-at-old-delorean-plant-in-belfast-1.2397970 |archive-date=July 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The company had originally intended to build the factory in [[Puerto Rico]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cartype.com/pages/1145/delorean | title=Delorean | work=Cartype | access-date=February 20, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708122852/http://www.cartype.com/pages/1145/delorean | archive-date=July 8, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"ply\"/> but changed its plans when the [[Industrial Development Board for Northern Ireland]] (IDB) offered {{GBP|100 million}} (equivalent to about \u00a3{{inflation|UK|100|1981}}M in {{inflation/year|UK}}) towards it,<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/man.html |work=The DeLorean Museum |title=The man |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210031101/http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/man.html |archivedate=December 10, 2010 }}</ref> despite an assessment by consultants hired by the IDB that the business had only a 1-in-10 chance of success.<ref name=\"ply\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tech.plym.ac.uk/sme/interactive_resources/tutorials/failurecases/fd1.html | work=Failure as a design criterion | title=Failure of Design Management | access-date=February 20, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110213003610/http://www.tech.plym.ac.uk/sme/interactive_resources/tutorials/failurecases/fd1.html | archive-date=February 13, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:1982 De Lorean DMC12 coupe (8453073488).jpg|thumb|1982 DeLorean grey interior]]\nConstruction on the factory began in October 1978, and although production of the DeLorean was scheduled to start in 1979, engineering problems and [[cost overrun|budget overruns]] delayed production until late 1980. By the time production began the unemployment rate was high in Northern Ireland, and local residents lined up to apply for jobs at the factory. The workers were largely inexperienced, but were paid premium wages and supplied with the best equipment available.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ibrahim | first=Jeremy Ethan | title=The Story of John DeLorean - Falling from Grace | website=DriveTribe | date=2020-01-14 | url=https://drivetribe.com/p/the-story-of-john-delorean-falling-HQqcOKf-ScilqBw0Wrum9Q | access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=John DeLorean: A visionary or a charlatan? | website=The Irish Times | date=2013-03-21 | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/john-delorean-a-visionary-or-a-charlatan-1.2488641 | access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nDeLoreans had numerous mechanical problems and suffered from poor build quality. Most quality issues were solved by 1982, and the cars were sold from dealers with a one-year, {{convert|12000|mi|adj=on}} warranty.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.entermyworld.com/cat/dhistory/collectibles/facts-pamphlet/factsj1x1.jpg |website=www.entermyworld.com |title=facts pamphlet (Warranties, Dimensions, Suppliers) |access-date=August 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325051312/http://www.entermyworld.com/cat/dhistory/collectibles/facts-pamphlet/factsj1x1.jpg |archive-date=March 25, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean Motor Company filed [[bankruptcy]] in October 1982<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/26/business/delorean-motor-files-bankruptcy.html</ref>.  Approximately 100 partially assembled DeLoreans on the production line were completed by [[Big Lots|Consolidated International]].  The remaining parts from the factory stock, the parts from the US Warranty Parts Center, as well as parts from the original suppliers that had not yet been delivered to the factory were all shipped to [[Columbus, Ohio]] in 1983\u201384.  A company called KAPAC sold these parts to retail and [[wholesaling|wholesale]] customers by mail order.  In 1997, DeLorean Motor Company of Texas acquired this inventory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/q&a.asp#whereparts |title=DeLorean Motor Company FAQ |publisher=Delorean.com |date=November 6, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121215155/http://delorean.com/q%26a.asp |archivedate=November 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nProduction information was lost or scattered upon the [[DeLorean Motor Company#Downturn and bankruptcy|shutdown of DMC]] and production figures for the DeLorean have never been verified based on official factory records.  Despite some unexplained VIN gaps, based upon VIN information, owners have been able to piece together the approximate quantity of DeLoreans produced.\n\nIn February 1982, DMC was placed into [[receivership]] and the factory continued to operate at a reduced production rate until the end of May.  When Consolidated International acquired the unsold and partially assembled cars in November 1982, it brought back workers to complete the cars remaining on the assembly line. It was decided to make the remaining completed 1982 model year cars into 1983 models. The remaining cars VINs were re-VINed into 1983 cars by taking the original VIN number and adding 5000 to it and changing the \"CD\" in the middle of the VIN to \"DD\" thus making a 1983 model.<ref name=\"Citizen Kidd\"/>\n\nFor the 1981 model year, there were 6,700 DeLoreans produced (VIN 500-7199).  For the 1982 model year, there were 1,999 DeLoreans produced (VIN 10001-11999).  For the 1983 model year, there were 276 DeLoreans (VIN 17000-17170 and 20001-20105) bringing the total estimated production to 8,975 cars.<ref name=\"Citizen Kidd\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.citizenkidd.com/DMC/pages/viN.asp |title=Texas DeLorean Club |access-date=June 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218154415/http://www.citizenkidd.com/DMC/pages/viN.asp |archive-date=December 18, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2007, about 6,500 DeLorean cars were thought to still exist.<ref>{{cite news |first= Martin |last= Zimmerman |url= https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |title= For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |accessdate= January 7, 2013 |work= Los Angeles Times |date= July 28, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130228154343/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |archive-date= February 28, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nThe DeLorean features a number of unusual construction details, including gull-wing doors, unpainted [[stainless-steel]] body panels, and a rear-mounted engine.\n\n===Body===\n[[File:De Lorean DMC-12 at Wollaton Park, Nottingham, England.jpg|thumb|The gull-wing doors on the DeLorean were a distinctive feature.]]\nThe body design of the DeLorean was a product of [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] of [[Italdesign Giugiaro|Ital Design]] and is panelled in brushed [[AISI steel grades#Stainless steel|SS304]] stainless steel. Except for three cars plated in 24-karat gold, all DeLoreans left the factory uncovered by paint or clearcoat.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Body Finish and Composition from Owners Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110228223225/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |archive-date= February 28, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Painted DeLoreans do exist, although these were all painted after the cars were purchased from the factory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |title=DeLorean Prototype & Production |publisher=AACA Museum |date= |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606022652/https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In order to train the workforce, a small number of DeLoreans were produced without the costly stainless steel panels and are referred to as \"black cars\" or \"mules\" in reference to their black fiberglass bodies. These cars were never intended to be sold.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |title=DeLorean - DeLorean DMC-12 Technical (1981-1982) |publisher=Motor-car.net |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425053807/https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSmall scratches in the stainless-steel body panels can be removed with a non-metallic scouring pad (since metal pads can leave iron particles embedded in the stainless steel, which can give the appearance of the stainless \"rusting\"), or even sandpaper.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Care & Feeding: Stainless Steel Body Maintenance |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110515142238/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |archive-date= May 15, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> The stainless-steel panels are fixed to a [[fiberglass]] underbody. The underbody is affixed to a steel double-Y frame chassis, inspired by the [[Lotus Esprit]] platform.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nThe unpainted stainless body creates challenges during [[Automotive restoration|restoration]] of the cars. In traditional automotive body repair, the panel is repaired to be as original (\"straight\") as possible, and imperfections are sculpted back to form with polyester body filler like [[Bondo (putty)|Bondo]] or lead (body [[solder]]). This poses no problem (aside from originality) with most cars, as the filler will be hidden by the car's paint (for example, most new cars have filler hiding the seam where the roof meets the [[quarter panel]]). With an unpainted stainless body, the stainless steel must be reworked to exactly the original shape, contour, and grain, which is a tremendously difficult job on regular steel (a dented or bent panel is stretched, and a shrinking hammer or other techniques must be used to unstretch the metal) and even more difficult with stainless due to its tendency to [[Work hardening|work-harden]]. Furthermore, it is exceedingly difficult to paint stainless steel due to difficulties with paint adhesion. DeLorean envisioned that damaged panels would simply be replaced rather than repaired.\n\nAnother distinctive feature of the DeLorean is its [[gull-wing door]]s. The common problem of supporting the weight of gull-wing doors was solved by other manufacturers with lightweight doors in the [[Mercedes-Benz 300SL]] and a hydraulic pump in the [[Bricklin SV-1]], although these designs had structural or convenience disadvantages. The DeLorean features heavy doors supported by [[Cryogenics|cryogenically]] preset [[Torsion bar suspension|torsion bars]] and gas-charged [[strut]]s.<ref>{{US patent|4,378,658}}</ref> These torsion bars were developed by [[Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation|Grumman Aerospace]] (and built by Unbrako in the UK, a division of SPS Technologies of Jenkintown, Pennsylvania, US) to withstand the stresses of supporting the doors.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Exotic Technology |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511091013/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |archive-date= May 11, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Much like the [[scissor doors|doors]] fitted to the [[Lamborghini Countach]], the DeLorean doors featured small cutout windows, because full-sized windows would not be fully retractable within the short door panels. Additionally, the doors featured red and amber \"safety\" lights around the perimeter. These lights illuminated when the door was open and could be seen from the front, rear or side of the vehicle at night or in low-light situations.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Vehicle Dimensions from Technical Manual, Workshop Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090401070948/http://dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |archive-date= April 1, 2009 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Door Design |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100914111250/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |archive-date= September 14, 2010 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Engine and drivetrain===\nThe [[engine]] is a [[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]] ([[V6 PRV engine|PRV]]) {{cvt|2849|cc|L|2|order=flip}} [[V6 engine|V6]], rated at {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm and [[torque]] of {{convert|153|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 2750 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|website=carfolio.com|title=1981 De Lorean DMC-12 specifications|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614071722/https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1982/587540/de_lorean_dmc-12.html|website=automobile-catalog.com|title=1982 De Lorean DMC-12 specs|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> that was designed and built under special contract with the [[DeLorean Motor Company]]. These PRVs were a development of the 2.7-litre V6 in the [[Renault 30]] and were built in the PRV Factory in [[Douvrin]], Northern France. The 5-speed [[manual transmission]], also designed by PRV, was built at the [[Renault]] facility near [[Caen]] in [[Normandy]]. The engines and [[gearbox]]es were shipped weekly by sea from the PRV factories to the DMC factory.\n\n===Suspension===\nThe [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] is a four-wheel [[independent suspension]], [[coil spring]]s, and telescopic [[shock absorbers]]. The front suspension uses [[Double wishbone suspension|double wishbones]], while the rear is a [[Multi-link suspension|multi-link]] setup.\n\nWhen the DeLorean first arrived in the US, the car had a higher than expected wheel gap in the front suspension.  The nose-high appearance is the result of poor quality coil springs.  Despite having significantly less weight in the front, the front and rear springs had the same spring rate and also used lower quality steel which resulted in the nose-high look.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 | pages = 83}}</ref>  Some people have erroneously cited a last minute change in US bumper height requirements led DMC to raise the vehicle just prior to delivery, however this is not true.  Design drawings clearly show that the design met [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration|NHTSA]] minimum bumper and headlight heights of the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/Bumper/Index.html|title=Bumper Q&A's|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003151011/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/bumper/index.html|archive-date=October 3, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|title=DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 49 CFR Part 571, [Docket No. 01-8885; Notice 01], RIN 2127-AH81, Glare from headlamps and other Front Mounted Lamps, Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard No. 108; Lamps, Reflective Devices, and Associated Equipment|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927155258/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Many owners have subsequently replaced or modified the front springs to return the front height to the original design specification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|title=Improving handling and lowering the DeLorean - DeLorean Motor Company|author=|date=|website=support.delorean.com|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621093431/http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSteering is [[rack and pinion]], with an overall [[steering ratio]] of 14.9:1, giving 2.65 turns lock-to-lock and a {{convert|35|ft|m|adj=on}} turning circle. DeLoreans are fitted with [[alloy|cast alloy]] wheels, measuring {{convert|14|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|6|in|mm}} wide on the front and {{convert|15|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|8|in|mm}} wide on the rear. These were fitted with [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] NCT steel-belted radial tires. The DeLorean is a [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-engine vehicle]] with a 35%\u201365% front\u2013rear weight distribution.<ref>{{cite web|first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_weight.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Weight and Balance from Technical manual |publisher=Dmcnews.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean features power-assisted [[disc brake]]s on all wheels, with {{convert|10|in|mm|adj=on}} rotors front and {{convert|10.5|in|mm|adj=on}} rear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|title=1981 DeLorean-17|author=|date=|website=oldcarbrochures.org|access-date=May 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524222200/http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAt the time of release, the automotive press was generally complimentary towards the DeLorean.  [[Motor Trend]]<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 128\u2013129}}</ref>, [[Car and Driver]] <ref>https://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/comparison-test/a15144078/de-lorean-vs-chevy-corvette-datsun-280-zx-ferrari-308gts-porsche-911-comparison-test/</ref> and [[Road_%26_Track|Road & Track]]<ref>https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/</ref> had mostly positive remarks about the car.  All of them noted disappointing performance especially those that performed comparative tests against other vehicles but were otherwise impressed with the car noting commendable gas mileage most of them noting that the DeLorean is more of a GT car rather than a sports car or racecar.\n\nHowever, more recent reviews of the car have been much more harsh.  [[Time Magazine]] included the DeLorean on its list of 50 worst cars of all time in 2017.<ref>https://time.com/4723114/50-worst-cars-of-all-time/</ref>  In his book ''Naff Motors: 101 Automotive Lemons'', Tony Davis described the build quality as \"woeful\".  ''Top Gear'' writer Richard Porter included it in his book ''Crap Cars'', calling it \"dismal\",<ref name = \"Porter\">{{cite book|last=Porter |first=Richard |title=Crap Cars |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2005 |isbn= |page=}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nDMC's comparison literature noted that the DeLorean could achieve {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|}} in 8.8 seconds, when equipped with a manual transmission. When equipped with an automatic transmission, the DeLorean would accelerate from {{convert|0|to|60|mph|}} in 10.5 seconds as tested by ''Road & Track'' magazine. The car's top speed is {{convert|109|mph|0}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|title=1982 DeLorean DMC-12: The Vintage Road & Track Test|date=October 21, 2015|work=Road & Track|publisher=|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803211950/http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|archive-date=August 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Road and Track called the car: \".. not quick for a sports/GT car in this price category ..\".\n\n==Problems and issues==\nDeLoreans, early production models in particular, suffered from poor build quality as well as mechanical issues with the vehicle.  Early production cars needed as much as 140-200 hours of work at DMC Quality Assurance Centers prior to being shipped to dealerships for delivery. DMC eventually sent 30 factory workers to the quality centers in the US to learn about the issues and how to fix them.  Quality issues did improve over time and by 1982 many of the quality issues had been resolved.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 83 - 84}}</ref>\n\nA total of four recalls were issued by the factory to correct issues such as a sticking throttle, front suspension issues and an inertia switch. <ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 108\u2013109}}</ref>\n\nOther quality issues that plagued the car included other issues surrounding the front suspension, clutch pedal adjustment (or lack thereof), brake rotors, instruments; in particular the [[speedometer]], power door locks and weak alternators.  Many early DeLoreans were delivered with an incorrect alignment with the toe-in incorrectly set leading to premature tire wear. \n\nIn addition, many dealers were reluctant to perform warranty work on DeLoreans since DMC owed them money for past warranty claims that were still unpaid.  Some dealerships were not able to perform repair work properly as DMC never issued a proper service manual.  The lack of quality service at dealerships was a point of frustration for many DeLorean owners at the time, particularly those who paid over sticker price to purchase one of the first cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 111\u2013112}}</ref>\n\n==Pricing and options==\n\nUpon release in 1981, a DeLorean had a suggested retail price of US$25,000 ($650 more when equipped with an [[automatic transmission]]); this is equivalent to approximately US${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|25000|1981}}}} in {{inflation-year|US}}.{{inflation-fn|US}}. MSRP would increase in 1982 to $29,825<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|title=1982 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616231331/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and again in 1983 to $34,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|title=1983 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015225/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> At the outset, there were extensive waiting lists of people willing to pay up to $10,000 above the list price; however, after the collapse of the DeLorean Motor Company, unsold cars could be purchased for less than the retail price.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_sales.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Sales and Dealer Experiences}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean was only available with two factory options; a no-cost [[manual transmission]] or automatic transmission and the choice of a grey or black interior (grey interior became available mid 1981 model year).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |title=one of one! factory burgundy interior delorean |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905044903/https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The standard feature list included stainless-steel body panels; gull-wing doors with cryogenically treated torsion bars; leather seats; [[air conditioning]]; an AM/FM [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] [[stereo system]]; [[power window]]s, [[power door locks|locks]] and [[Power side-view mirror|mirrors]]; a tilt and telescopic [[steering wheel]]; tinted glass; body side moldings; intermittent/constant windshield wipers; and an electric rear-window defogger. Several dealer options were available, including a car cover; [[Sheepskin seat cover|sheepskin]] seat covers; floor mats; car care cleaning kit; black textured accent stripes; grey scotch-cal accent stripes; a luggage rack and a ski-rack adapter.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Dealer Installed Accessories |date= June 20, 1981 |access-date= January 27, 2005 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/6HxeVWMtL?url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |archive-date= July 8, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |title= DeLorean Owners Association: DeLorean specifications table |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980214030500/http://delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |archivedate=February 14, 1998}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=390 | image1=DMC Sticker.jpg |width1=199 |height1=260 |alt1=1982 DMC-12 window sticker |image2=DMC12 clearance.jpg |width2=200 |height2=260 |alt2=DeLorean clearance advertisement |footer_align=center |footer=1982 window sticker & 1983 DeLorean clearance advertisement}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Production changes==\nAlthough there were no typical yearly updates to the DeLorean, several changes were made to the DeLorean during production.<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\"/>  Instead of making changes at the end of the model year, DMC implemented changes mid-production. This resulted in no clear distinction between the 1981, 1982, and 1983 model years, but with subtle changes taking place almost continuously throughout the life cycle of the DeLorean.\n\n===Hood styles===\nThe original [[hood (vehicle)|hood]] of the DeLorean had [[Groove (machining)|grooves]] running down both sides. It included a tank flap to simplify [[Filling station|fuel filling]]. These cars typically had a locking cap to prevent fuel theft by [[siphon]]ing. In August 1981, the hood flap was removed from the hood of the cars (although the hood creases remained). This style was retained well into 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |title=The DeLorean |publisher=Babb Technology |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=November 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Based on production numbers for all three years, this hood style is probably the most common. After the supply of locking caps was exhausted, the company switched to a non-locking version (resulting in at least 500 cars with no flap, but with locking caps). The final styling for the hood included the addition of a DeLorean name badge and the removal of the grooves, resulting in a completely flat hood. According to senior personnel who worked at the Dunmurry factory, initial elimination of flapped hoods has a simple if unglamorous explanation; Chuck Benington, managing director, did not like the design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Sutton, Purchasing Manager, Dunmurry factory|url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132250/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|archive-date=April 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=600 |image1=Early 1981 De Lorean hood.jpg |width1=387 |height1=142 |alt1=Early 1981 hood |image2=1983 De Lorean hood.jpg |width2=414 |height2=162 |alt2=1983 hood |footer_align=center |footer=Side-by-side comparison of an early 1981 hood (left) vs. a later model 1983 hood (right)}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Other changes===\n[[File:De Lorean add-on Pull strap.jpg|thumb|Early pull strap]]\n[[File:Delorean dmc-12 later style side bolster.jpg|thumb|Later-style one-piece bolster]]\n[[File:mid 1981 De Lorean silver wheel.JPG|thumb|Mid-1981 silver wheel]]\n\nJohn DeLorean was {{height|ft=6|in=4}} tall, and he designed the car to comfortably fit someone of his stature.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|title= The DeLorean's Time Leap|author= Claire Suddath|publisher= [[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date= April 19, 2012|access-date= July 14, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140706011419/http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|archive-date= July 6, 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> For shorter people, the addition of a pull strap made closing the doors much easier from the inside. These attach to the existing door handle. Late-model 1981 cars, and all cars from 1982 and 1983, have doors with integrated pull straps.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\">{{cite web|url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|title=DeLorean \u2013 The Car: Production Changes|work=babbtechnology.com|access-date=August 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe side [[bolster]]ing in the DeLorean was originally separate from the main interior pieces. In cars with this construction, is a tendency to place pressure on this piece when entering and exiting the vehicle, which eventually causes the bolstering to separate from the trim panel. To solve this problem, cars built in and after late 1981 have one solid trim piece with the bolster permanently attached.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nAs an addition to later cars, a foot rest, or [[dead pedal]], was added to help prevent [[fatigue (physical)|fatigue]] while driving. This is one of the few changes that is directly tied to a model year. These were built into only a few of the late-1981 vehicles and were added to all cars starting with 1982 production.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\"/>\n\nAlthough the styling of the DeLorean's wheels remained unchanged, the wheels of early-model 1981 vehicles were painted grey. These wheels sported matching grey centre caps with an embossed DMC logo. Early into the 1981 production run, these were changed to a polished silver look, with a contrasting black center cap. The embossed logo on the center caps was painted silver to add contrast.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the DeLorean came with an AM/FM stereo radio with cassette made by Craig. Since the Craig radio did not have a built-in clock, one was installed in front of the [[gear shift]] on the console. DeLorean switched to an ASI stereo in the middle of the 1982 production run. Since the ASI radio featured an on-board clock, the clock on the console was removed at the same time.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 44\u201345}}</ref>\n\nThe first 2,200 cars produced used a windshield-embedded [[antenna (radio)|antenna]]. This type of antenna proved to be unsuitable with poor radio reception. Oftentimes the radio would continually \"seek\", attempting to find a signal. A standard whip antenna, which was later changed to a manually retractable antenna, was added to the outside of the front right fender. While improving radio reception, this resulted in a hole in the stainless steel, and an unsightly antenna. As a result, the antenna was again moved. The final antenna was an automatic retractable version installed under the rear induction grill behind the rear driver's-side window.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 28\u201329}}</ref>\n\nThe small [[visor|sun visors]] on the DeLorean have [[Polyvinyl chloride|vinyl]] on one side and headliner [[Textile|fabric]] on the other side. Originally these were installed such that the headliner side would be on the bottom when not in use. Later on in 1981, they were reversed so that the vinyl side would be on the bottom.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 40}}</ref>\n\nThe original 80 amp Ducellier [[Alternator (auto)|alternator]] supplied with the early-production DeLoreans could not provide enough [[electric current|current]] to supply the car when all lights and electrical options were on; as a result, the [[battery (electricity)|battery]] would gradually discharge, leaving the driver stranded on the road. Beginning with cars built in late 1981, DeLoreans were fitted from the factory with a 90 amp [[Motorola]] alternator, which solved this problem. Additional battery drainage problems were caused by faulty or improperly adjusted door jamb switches. This switch activated the \"safety\" lights located around the door perimeter when it was open. When the door was closed, the door seals prevented the light from being seen. Due to the faulty switches the lights remained on, draining the battery. This happened to DeLorean owner [[Johnny Carson]] shortly after he was presented with the vehicle.\n\n==Notable and unique DeLoreans==\n\n===Prototypes and pilot cars===\nOnly one of two DeLorean prototypes still exists.<ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |publisher=DeLorean PJ Grady Europe |title=Delorean Repairs |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421053458/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Prototype 1 sold at the bankruptcy auction in 1984 for $37,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |title=DeLorean prototype cars sell at auction for total $58,000 |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602233213/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The car remained in a private collection until 2005 when it was sold to the owner of DeLorean Motor Company of Florida (DMCFL) where it received a complete restoration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |title=1587: 1976 DeLorean DMC-12 Original Prototype |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602234250/https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Proto 1 is now on display at DMCFL. Proto 2 was sent to [[Lotus Cars]] for development and evaluation in 1978. It was reported to have been destroyed in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Car |url=http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |website=The Delorean Museum |publisher=The Delorean Museum |accessdate=October 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006112343/http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |archivedate=October 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 28 pilot cars were built by DMC. The pilot cars are best identified by the subtly different interiors and sliding side windows. These cars, used for evaluation and regulatory testing of the DeLorean, were previously thought to have been destroyed. Subsequently, several of the pilot cars were found to have survived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |title=Earliest known Pilot car found/photographed |publisher=Dmctalk.org |date=November 5, 1955 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132601/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |archive-date=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |title=Pilot Chronology |publisher=Pjgrady.co.uk |date=November 24, 1980 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051421/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Pilot car 25 which was featured on the front cover of [[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]] in 1981 was found in 2003 in a barn in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |title=pilot-25 |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905040305/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Visioneering car===\nWith the 1980 [[National Automobile Dealers Association|NADA]] meeting approaching, DMC planned to show a final \u201cproduction\u201d version of the DeLorean, however there were no production cars ready at the time or even any production stainless steel panels.\n\nEarlier, in the summer of 1979, the revised Giugiaro styling mock-up was shipped to Visioneering, a [[Detroit]] based company, to create data needed to make the stamping dies for the stainless panels. This project would expand to create dies used to create a \u201cproduction\u201d car for the NADA show.\n\nUsing a prototype chassis supplied by Lotus in late 1979, Visioneering completed the assembly of this car at a cost of $750,000. The car was presented at the 1980 NADA show and was later used for engineering development and technical training as well as press photos. The Visioneering car would eventually be sold at the bankruptcy auction in late 1984 for $21,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\"/> Today, the car is in a private collection.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage| ISBN = 978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2012 | page = 108}}</ref>\n\n===Legend turbo cars===\nIt was determined that the DeLorean needed additional power when automotive magazine road tests showed {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|abbr=on}} times for the DeLorean between 9.5 and 10.5 seconds, while its rivals were in the 7.5\u20138.5 second range. There had been interest in [[turbocharger|turbocharging]] the DeLorean early on, but the DMC engineering staff was busy with other projects, so DeLorean decided to go outside to develop a turbocharged version of the DeLorean.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\">{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion | isbn=0-9744141-0-7 | author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |date= 2003 | pages = 110\u2013111}}</ref>\n\nHaving had previous success with turbocharging [[Fiat 124 Sport Spider|Fiat Spiders]], DeLorean entered into a contract with Legend Industries, based in [[Hauppauge, New York|Hauppauge]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. DMC wanted to increase power without sacrificing fuel efficiency. DMC wanted a wide power band and did not want a surge of power similar to the [[Porsche 930]] Turbo. Legend used twin [[IHI Corporation|IHI]] RHB52 turbos along with twin [[intercooler]]s. The results were an engine capable of accelerating smoothly in fifth gear from 1,500&nbsp;rpm to full turbo boost at 2,500&nbsp;rpm, reaching {{convert|150|mph|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\" />\n[[File:Legend engine.jpg|thumb|Legend Twin Turbo setup from VIN 530]]\n\nIn addition, Legend Industries developed a single turbocharged setup that was never finished.\nThe company converted a total of four DeLoreans and two Renault Alpines, which were the first development cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|title=Delorean Car Sales Europe UK. Canvey Island Essex SS8 OPQ|publisher=|access-date=February 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513040331/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|archive-date=May 13, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[VIN]] 530 was written in numerous press articles as the fastest production car of its era.\n\nIn a test run of VIN 530 at [[Bridgehampton Race Circuit|Bridgehampton Raceway]] in 1981, the twin-turbo DeLorean was quicker than a [[Ferrari 308 GTB/GTS|Ferrari 308]] and a [[Porsche 928]]. It has been a misconception for many years that VIN 502 was at Bridgehampton and used in testing; however, evidence from pictures, along with information from a Legend employee published by PJ Grady, indicates that 530 was used along with VIN 558.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |title=identifying-the-legend-cars |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905041236/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By the time of Bridgehampton, Legend had perfected modular boosting, which the earlier prototypes did not have installed apart from one of the Alpine mules and VIN 530.<ref>{{cite web | title=DeLorean DMC-12 | website=Silodrome | date=March 3, 2018 | url=https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | access-date=September 5, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905042552/https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | archive-date=September 5, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVIN 530 tested 0\u201360&nbsp;mph in 5.8 seconds and the [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] in 14.7 seconds. John DeLorean was so impressed with the engine, he committed to ordering 5,000 engines from Legend Industries. DMC planned to offer a turbocharged engine as a $7,500 option in 1984 (presumably to compete with the newly redesigned [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|1984 Corvette]]). Before any of the 5,000 cars could be put into production, DMC had declared bankruptcy, which drove Legend Industries, as well as other suppliers, into bankruptcy.<ref name=\"DeLorean Gold Portfolio\">{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Gold Portfolio | author=R. M. Clarke| publisher = Brookland Books LTD. |ISBN=1-85520-331-6 |date= 1996 | pages = 137\u2013143}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" Style=\"text-align:center\"\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n!\tVIN\t!!\tConfiguration\t!!\tLast known location\t!!\tComments\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t502\t||\tTwin\t||\tNew Zealand\t||\tOriginal prototype\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t528\t||\tSingle\t||\tNew York\t||\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t530\t||\tTwin\t||\tUnited Kingdom\t||\tSister twin-turbo\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t558\t||\tSingle\t||\tUnknown\t||\t\n|}\n\n===Gold-plated===\n[[File:gold-D.jpg|thumb|A gold-plated DeLorean in Reno, Nevada]]\nFor Christmas 1980, a DeLorean/[[American Express]] promotion planned to sell 100 [[Karat|24K]]-[[Gilding|gold-plated]] DeLoreans for US$85,000 each to its gold-card members, but only two were sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|title=In 1980, You Could Buy an $85,000, 24K-Gold-Plated DeLorean|publisher=|access-date=September 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920152935/http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> One of these was purchased by Roger Mize, president of Snyder National Bank in [[Snyder, Texas]]. VIN #4301 sat in the bank lobby for over 20 years before being loaned to the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]] in [[Los Angeles]]. It has a black interior and an automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |title=The 24-Karat Gold Plated DeLorean Car |publisher=Bigtexas.com |accessdate=January 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224111825/http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe second gold-plated American Express DeLorean was purchased by Sherwood Marshall, an entrepreneur and former [[Royal Canadian Navy|Royal Canadian Naval]] Officer. Marshall donated his DeLorean to the [[William F. Harrah]] Foundation/[[National Automobile Museum]] in [[Reno, Nevada]]. This car, VIN #4300, is the only one of the three existing gold-plated cars to be equipped with a manual transmission. It has a saddle-brown interior and, like its golden siblings, is a low-mileage vehicle with only {{convert|1442|mi}} on the [[odometer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.automuseum.org |title=National Automobile Museum |publisher=National Automobile Museum |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207005657/http://www.automuseum.org/ |archive-date=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA third gold-plated car exists with {{convert|636|mi}} on the odometer; it carries the VIN plate for the last DeLorean, #20105, although final assembly was actually completed in Columbus, Ohio, in 1983.<ref name=bigtexas>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Gold DeLorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Bigtexas.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110812111029/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/|archivedate=August 12, 2011 }}</ref> This car was assembled with spare parts that were required by American Express in case one of the other two that were built were damaged and all necessary gold-plated parts were on hand, with the exception of one door. Thus the car was assembled after another door was gold-plated, though the added door does not precisely match the rest of the car in color and grain. The car was first acquired by the winner of a [[Big Lots]] store raffle. Consolidated International, which owned the department store, had purchased 1374 DeLoreans during the DeLorean Motor Company's financial troubles, acquiring the remaining stock after the company went into receivership. Now held by a private owner in [[La Vale, Maryland]], this third and last gold-plated DeLorean was for sale online at a price of US$250,000, but remains unsold.<ref name=bigtexas/> After being offered for sale for over a decade, it is unclear whether it has sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Delorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Archive.is |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524094241/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |archivedate=May 24, 2012 }}</ref> This car and the example in Reno have saddle-brown leather interiors, a color scheme which was intended to become an option on later-production cars, however, these two cars were the only DeLoreans to ever be equipped with these factory parts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://support.delorean.com/kb/a10/interior-colors-carpets-and-parts.aspx |title=interior-colors-carpets-and-parts |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905043350/http://support.delorean.com/kb/a10/interior-colors-carpets-and-parts.aspx |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA gold-plated DeLorean was reproduced privately by an enthusiast.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |title=Gold Plated DeLoreans? \u2013 Yes There Were Four |publisher=Mycarquest.com |date=February 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051720/http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |archive-date=April 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Right-hand-drive models===\nDeLoreans were primarily intended for the American market. All production models were therefore [[left-hand-drive]]. Evidence survives from as early as April 1981, however, that the DeLorean Motor Company was aware of the need to produce a [[right-hand-drive]] (RHD) version to supply to world markets, specifically the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |title=woller-hodec |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905043041/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company faced the choice of building right-hand-drive models from scratch or performing a post-production conversion exercise. Given the cost of new body molds, tooling, and a host of specific parts that a factory-built right-hand-drive configuration would require, the company opted to investigate the idea of a post-production conversion using a UK company based in [[Hampshire]] called Wooler-Hodec Ltd.<ref>{{cite book | last=Narus | first=D. | title=Independent Sports Cars | publisher=Lulu.com | year=2017 | isbn=978-1-387-15601-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HolUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA48 | access-date=August 30, 2019 | page=48}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[File:De Lorean DMC12 - Flickr - foshie (1).jpg|thumb|RHD DeLorean]]\nOnly 16 right-hand-drive factory-authorized DeLoreans were ever produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |title=DeLorean: Euro Spec DeLoreans |publisher=Deloreans.co.uk |accessdate=May 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617185502/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010 }}</ref> These cars can be divided into two distinct groups:\n# The first batch, known by enthusiasts as the \"Wooler-Hodec cars\", were converted by the UK company of that name. Evidence still exists in the form of a DMC factory memo, which orders 20 cars to be converted to right-hand drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |title=DMC Inter-Office Memo: RHD Conversion Programme |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905045408/https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to the factory's closure, this order was never completed, and today a total of 13 cars survive, carrying the VINs 510, 12171\u201312181 and 12199. VIN 510 is understood to be the first of this batch of cars converted and was later sold at the factory auction in 1984. The other 12 cars were auctioned off by the receivers in early 1983. As a result, several of these cars were registered at the same time and have the Northern Irish registration (license) number \"SIJ xxxx\". All of this first batch of cars had a black interior and all had manual transmission, except VIN 12175. This car is the only factory-authorized right-hand-drive black-interior automatic car and is owned by Andrew Withers, former editor of the UK DeLorean Owners Club.\n# The second batch were registered and used by the factory in Northern Ireland, with registration numbers (license plates), AXI 1697, AXI 1698, AXI 1699 and are referred to by enthusiasts as the \"AXI cars\". These three cars (VINs 5565, 5592 and 5638) differ from the first Wooler-Hodec cars in several ways. They all had roof-mounted radio antennas, indicator repeater lights, no side marker lights, white forward-facing door lights, fog-light switch, and textured body rubstrips on the stainless panels. No [[catalytic converters]] or [[Oxygen sensor|lambda equipment]] were fitted, as British legislation did not require them. VIN 5565 with the registration number AXI 1697 was a fully UK homologated example, which was shown at the British motor show at Birmingham, UK in October 1982. It includes a unique rearward-facing twin exhaust, no catalytic converters and the UK-specification engine as used by Volvo, but retaining the usual Renault ancillaries. The transmission final drive was also set at 3.88:1 versus the standard 3.44:1. Attention was paid to other unique details such as correctly offset wing mirrors.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nA common misconception surrounding the factory-authorized right-hand-drive DeLoreans is that they were all fitted with different, so-called \"Euro-spec\", tail lights<ref name=\"rubberlight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating so-called \"Euro-spec\" tail light unit |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223141/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> as part of the right-hand-drive conversion program. This is not the case. Due to the nature of these cars as prototypes, they were not officially type-approved for use in the UK. Owners who bought these cars at auction in the early 1980s encountered difficulty in registering them as new vehicles in the UK. At this point a former DeLorean Motor Cars executive offered to modify and register the cars so that they could be used in the UK. These modifications included:\n* Different seat-belt units fitted.<ref name=\"foglight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified seat belt unit in right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223213/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of Rubbolite tail light clusters with a built-in fog light function.<ref name=\"rubberlight\"/>\n* The fitting of a fog light switch to one of the center-console dummy switches.<ref name=\"foglight\"/>\n* A custom-made tail light surround and number (license) plate bezel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating custom fabricated tail light and number (license) plate bezel fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223225/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the front turn signal lenses for ones of a different, more rounded style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating rounded turn signal lens on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013912/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the rear side marker lenses for amber ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating amber rear side marker lens fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223301/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThere were a number of official alterations made to the right-hand-drive cars' lights. The extent of these modifications varies between the first batch of \"Wooler-Hodec\" cars and the later \"AXI\" cars:\n\nAll of the 13 Wooler-Hodec cars were modified to the OEM front turn-signal lens fixing method in order to make them fit flush with the front fascia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified front turn signal lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013859/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref> The cars' headlights were also changed for right-hand-drive spec lights that incorporate a UK sidelight feature. The rest of the lights appear to have been left untouched by Wooler-Hodec during the conversion process.\n\nBy contrast, the three AXI cars had further modifications to the amber front door lights, which were exchanged for clear lenses of the same style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating clear door light lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223348/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> Perhaps the most significant alteration on the AXI cars is the deletion of the front and rear side markers. These are replaced by a single small round European-style indicator side repeater, situated on the front wing (fender). The body rubstrips are also of a different configuration in order to cover the areas that would otherwise have had federal side marker lenses fitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified rubstrips and single round marker light |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223415/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===''Back to the Future''===\n{{Main|DeLorean time machine}}\n[[File:'81-'82 DeLorean DMC-12.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean \"time machine\" from the ''Back to the Future'' trilogy exhibited at [[Universal Studios Florida]]]]\nSeveral special-edition DeLorean cars have been produced over the years, and the car is most notably featured as the time machine in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' film trilogy]]. Six DeLorean chassis were used during the production, along with one manufactured out of fiberglass for scenes where a full-size DeLorean was needed to \"fly\" on-screen; only three of the cars still exist, with one that was destroyed at the end of ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]'', two additional cars were abandoned, and the fiberglass replica was scrapped. Universal Studios owns two of the remaining cars, occasionally putting them on display or using them for other productions, and the last resides in a private collection after having been extensively restored.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |title=BTTF3 DeLorean: Where Are They? |date= |accessdate=January 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005125859/http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |archive-date=October 5, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The official ''[[Back to the Future]]'' DeLorean can be viewed at the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |title=Petersen Automotive Museum |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320133259/http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |archivedate=March 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA number of production DeLoreans have been modified by the [[Automotive aftermarket|aftermarket]] into ''Back to the Future'' time machine replicas, whose bodies and interiors are modified to mirror the appearance and functions of the film cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|title=Bob's Prop Shop|work=bobspropshop.com|access-date=November 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016005640/http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|archive-date=October 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==DMC Texas==\n[[File:\" 12 - ITALY (Milan) Electro Vehicles Europe ( EVE ) DeLorean DMC-12.JPG|thumb|[[Electric car|All-electric model]] DMCev in Milan (2012)]]\nIn 1995, Stephen Wynne from Liverpool created a separate company based in Texas using the [[DeLorean Motor Company (Texas)|DeLorean Motor Company]] name. Wynne acquired the trademark on the stylized DMC logo, along with the remaining parts inventory of the original DeLorean Motor Company. The company rebuilds cars at its [[Humble, Texas]], location using a combination of [[new old stock]] (NOS) parts, original equipment manufacturer (OEM), and reproduction parts on a made-to-order basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103728/http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archivedate=July 18, 2011|title=New build cars|publisher=DeLorean Motor Company|accessdate=May 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDMC Texas (based in [[Humble, Texas]]) announced on July 30, 2007, that the car would be returning into very limited production (about 20 cars a year) in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |title=For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |work=LA Times |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310115947/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |archive-date=March 10, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> They were subsequently sued by John DeLorean's widow for illegally licensing the family name. DMC Texas settled this lawsuit in September 2015 by paying his widow an undisclosed sum and in turn received rights to use the name, images, and trademark in the future.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lawyers Settle DeLorean Lawsuit Just in Time for 'Back to the Future' Day|url = https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|website = WSJ Blogs \u2013 Law Blog|date = October 21, 2015|accessdate = December 26, 2015|first = Jacob|last = Gershman|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222085854/http://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|archive-date = December 22, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe cars were announced to have a new stainless-steel frame; with optional extras such as GPS, an enhanced \"Stage 2\" engine, and possibly a new modern interior. Given that the cars were made with 80% old parts,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |title=Texas Entrepreneur Set to Start Building DeLorean Cars |publisher=Fox News |date=August 21, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511132411/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |archive-date=May 11, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> the term \"return to production\" is something of a misnomer; the cars are constructed on DeLorean underbodies built by the original company in the 1980s and retaining their VINs. The cars' titles show the year of the underbody's manufacture. Therefore, they are not new DeLoreans, but complete rebuilds of the car from the underbody with enhancements. In 2009, the price of a refurbished DeLorean from DMC Texas started at US$57,500, and the project was featured in an episode of ''[[Modern Marvels]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|title=Anything But Rusty: Reviewing The DeLorean In 2009|first=Ryan|last=McCaffrey|publisher=Motor Authority|date=December 20, 2009|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222115538/http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2011, it was announced that an all-electric model would be available for sale by 2013. It was said to have a {{Convert|200|hp|0|abbr=on|adj=on}} motor, accelerate from {{Convert|0|to|60|mph|abbr=on|km/h}} in 8 seconds, and sell for US$90,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Fox News |date=October 18, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029024300/http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archivedate=October 29, 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |title=The New DeLorean EV Gets Some Test Runs by Enthusiasts |work=Automotive Discovery |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026195129/http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |archive-date=October 26, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Back To The Future: All Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Forbes |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101212905/http://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archive-date=November 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Initial test drives revealed that the prototype had a range of {{Convert|70|mi|km}}, approaching the {{Convert|100|mi|km}} that was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|title=Electric DeLorean: First Drive|first=Kevin|last=McCauley|publisher=Jalopnik|date=October 17, 2011|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025045755/http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|archive-date=October 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> However, 2014 saw criticism from fans who tried to buy the electric DeLorean only to learn that it was still unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|title=It Seems DeLorean Has Gone Back To The Past Again|first=Wes|last=Lungwitz|publisher=Car Debater|date=February 14, 2014|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106215825/http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|archive-date=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDue to the passage of the [[Low Volume Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Act of 2015|Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act]], DMC Texas announced that it would be producing replica DeLoreans with an expected release date in 2017. DMC anticipated building approximately 50 vehicles per year over six years with an estimated retail price of US$100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |title=The DeLorean Is Coming Back Thanks To This New Law, Will Have 300-400 HP |first=Jason |last=Torchinsky |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830195816/https://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |title=Brand-New DeLorean Replicas Are on the Way |date=January 27, 2016 |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914085258/https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |archive-date=September 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2016, DMC announced that it was expecting to build 12 units in the first production year with as many as 50 in the second year of production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |title=DMC Blog - DeLorean - The New DMC DeLorean |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827145747/http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |archive-date=August 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>   In December 2019, the NHTSA issued guidelines for the Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act<ref>https://www.nhtsa.gov/sites/nhtsa.dot.gov/files/documents/replica_vehicle_program_nprm_12172019.pdf</ref> and DMC Texas is now projecting they will begin production in 2021.<ref>https://www.autoblog.com/2020/01/24/delorean-motor-company-dmc-12-new-cars/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<!-- Dead note \"production2\": [http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/img/news/n_vinrat.pdf DMC-12 Estimated Production Volumes by Month] (PDF) by Knut Grimsrud -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/index.html DMC - The legend - DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean.hu/ - Delorean Club Hungary- DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |first1= John Z. |last1= DeLorean |first2= Ted |last2= Schwarz |title= DeLorean |location= Grand Rapids, MI |publisher= Zondervan |year= 1985 |isbn= 0-310-37940-7 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/delorean00delo }}\n* {{cite book |first= John |last= Lamm |title= DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion |edition= 2nd |year= 2003 |location= Fort Jones, CA |publisher= Red Lion Press |isbn= 0-9744141-0-7}}\n* {{cite book |first= R. M. |last= Clarke |title= DeLorean: 1977\u20131995 Gold Portfolio |year= 1995 |location= Cobham |publisher= Brooklands |isbn= 1-85520-331-6}}\n* {{cite book |first= James |last= Espey |title= The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | edition= 2nd |year= 2014 |publisher= the DeLorean Garage |isbn= 978-0-9856578-1-9}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris | last= Parnham |first2= Andrew | last2= Withers |title= DeLorean Celebrating the Impossible |year= 2015| location = | publisher= DeLorean Motor Cars (1978) Ltd.| isbn= 978-0-9928594-0-4}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris |last= Williams|title= DeLorean DMC-12 [sic], The Essential Buyers Guide (2018) |year=2018 | location= |publisher= Veloce Publishing| isbn= 978-1-787112-32-2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia |\n | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n | |\n | Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED. |\n | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details. |\n | |\n | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or |\n | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org) |\n | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template. |\n==={{No more links}}=========-->\n\n{{Commons category|DeLorean DMC-12}}\n* [http://www.delorean.com/ DeLorean Motor Company]\n* {{curlie|Recreation/Autos/Makes_and_Models/DeLorean/|DeLorean DMC-12}}\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=De Lorean|model=DMC 12|DeLorean DMC 12}}\n* [http://www.finecars.cc/en/detail/car/10075/ 1976 Concept DeLorean DMC 12]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_n_oBV2osAg ''The Car's the Star''] \u2013 TV biography of the DMC by former [[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]] host [[Quentin Willson]] (1999, UK)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Lotus}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Cars|North America}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeLorean}}\n[[Category:Cars of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n[[Category:Back to the Future]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with gull-wing doors]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with backbone chassis]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by rear-mounted 6-cylinder engines]]\n\n[[ja:\u30c7\u30ed\u30ea\u30a2\u30f3#DMC-12]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|1980s automobile}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = DMC DeLorean\n| image = Delorean DMC-12 side.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = 1983 DeLorean\n| manufacturer = [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC)<br />[[Bloomfield_Hills,_Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], Michigan, US\n| production = 9,080<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2015/12/19/delorean-book/77623204/|title=DeLoreans still ply the roads -- and memories|url-status=live}}</ref> (disputed)\n| model_years = 1981\u20131983\n| assembly = DeLorean Motor Cars, Ltd. (DMCL) [[Dunmurry]], [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland\n| designer = [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Italdesign]]\n| class = Sports car\n| body_style = 2-door coup\u00e9\n| related = \n| layout = Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| engine = {{convert|2849|cc|L|2|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[V6 PRV engine]] ''ZMJ-159''\n| powerout = {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|207|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| transmission = 5-speed manual<br/>3-speed automatic<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2413|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\">{{Cite book|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946\u20131975|publisher= Krause|isbn=0-87341-027-0|editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first= John A.}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4267|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| width = {{convert|1988|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| height = {{convert|1140|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors closed<br/>{{convert|1962|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors open<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date = 2014| pages = 16}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|1233|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| doors = Gullwing doors\n}}\n\nThe '''DMC DeLorean''' (often referred to simply as the \"'''DeLorean'''\", as it was the only model ever produced by the company) is a sports car manufactured by [[John DeLorean]]'s [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC) for the American market from 1981 to 1983. The car was designed by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] and stood out for its [[gull-wing door]]s and brushed stainless-steel outer body panels, as well as an innovative fiberglass body structure with a steel backbone chassis. It became widely known for its disappointing lack of power and performance, which did not match the expectations created by its looks and price tag, but it became iconic for its appearances as the [[DeLorean time machine|time machine]] in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' media franchise]] after 1985.\n\nThroughout production, the car was generally unchanged, although minor modifications were made to such parts as the hood and wheels. The first production car was completed on January 21, 1981. About 9,000 DeLoreans were made before production halted in late December 1982 shortly after DMC had filed for bankruptcy.\n\n==History==\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 (9979) (cropped).jpg|thumb|A DeLorean with the gull-wing doors closed]]\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 with doors open.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean from the front with the gull-wing doors open]]\nIn October 1976, the first prototype DeLorean was completed by American automotive chief engineer William T. Collins, formerly chief engineer at [[Pontiac]].  Originally, the car was intended to have a centrally-mounted [[Wankel engine|Wankel rotary engine]].  The engine selection was reconsidered when [[Comotor]] production ended, and the favored engine became the [[Ford Cologne V6 engine]].  Eventually the French/Swedish [[fuel injection|fuel-injected]] [[V6 PRV engine]] ([[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]]) was selected.  Also the engine location moved from the mid-engined location in the prototype to a rear-engined installation in the production car.  The [[chassis]] was initially planned to be produced from a new and untested manufacturing technology known as elastic reservoir moulding (ERM), which would lighten the car while presumably lowering its production costs.  This new technology, for which DeLorean had purchased patent rights, was eventually found to be unsuitable.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nThese and other changes to the original concept led to considerable schedule pressures.  The entire car was deemed to require almost complete re-engineering, which was turned over to engineer [[Colin Chapman]], founder of [[Lotus Cars]].  Chapman replaced most of the unproven material and manufacturing techniques with those then employed by Lotus, like the steel backbone chassis.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003| pages = 71\u201375}}</ref>\n\nThe first prototype appeared in October 1976 and was known as the DSV-1, or DeLorean Safety Vehicle.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 23}}</ref> As development continued, the model was referred to as the DSV-12<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 28}}</ref> and later the DMC-12 since DMC was targeting a list price of US$12,000 ({{Inflation|US|12000|1976|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) at release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |title=DeLorean DMC-12 |access-date=February 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204065904/https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |archive-date=February 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html How an immigrant mechanic used $5 million to bring DeLoreans back to the future] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014534/https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html |date=February 4, 2019 }} Zack Guzman. 3:52 PM ET Wed, November 9, 2016</ref>\n\nAfter several delays and cost overruns, production finally began in late 1980. Around this time DMC officially dropped the name DMC-12 on its now US$25,000 ({{Inflation|US|25000|1981|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) car in favor of the model name DeLorean. The DeLorean sports car, as it was described in advertisements, began production in December 1980 with the first production car rolling off the assembly line on January 21, 1981.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lily Rothman |url=http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |title=DeLorean Auto History: What Happened to the Company |publisher=Time |date=January 21, 2016 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423164413/http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |title=Almanac: The DeLorean car |publisher=CBS News |date=January 21, 2018 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515122627/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |archive-date=May 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with James Espey of the new incarnation of the DeLorean Motor Company of [[Texas]], a drawing surfaced showing that the car originally had the potential to be named \"Z Tavio\".  John DeLorean's middle name and his son's first name were both Zachary, while Tavio was his father's name and his son's middle name.  Due to only sporadic documentation, there is little more that is currently known about the Z Tavio name and why it was ultimately rejected in favor of the DeLorean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |title=Interview with James Espy of DMCH |publisher=Myride.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908094456/http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |archive-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nConvincing Hollywood celebrities such as [[Johnny Carson]] and [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] to invest in the firm,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/21/business/21delorean.html | work=The New York Times | title=John Z. DeLorean, Father of Glamour Car, Dies at 80 | first=Danny | last=Hakim | date=March 21, 2005 | accessdate=May 1, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630061902/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/21/business/21delorean.html | archive-date=June 30, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theavanti.com/carson.htm |title=Avanti Celebrity Owners: Johnny Carson |publisher=Theavanti.com |date=May 22, 1992 |accessdate=May 4, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130210603/http://theavanti.com/carson.html|archivedate=November 30, 2010}}</ref> DMC eventually built the DeLorean in a factory in [[Dunmurry]], in [[Northern Ireland]], a neighborhood about {{Convert|10|km|0|abbr=on}} from the city of [[Belfast]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/manufacturing/bright-future-at-old-delorean-plant-in-belfast-1.2397970 |title=Bright future at old DeLorean plant in Belfast |publisher=Irishtimes.com |date=October 20, 2015 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710143132/https://www.irishtimes.com/business/manufacturing/bright-future-at-old-delorean-plant-in-belfast-1.2397970 |archive-date=July 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The company had originally intended to build the factory in [[Puerto Rico]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cartype.com/pages/1145/delorean | title=Delorean | work=Cartype | access-date=February 20, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708122852/http://www.cartype.com/pages/1145/delorean | archive-date=July 8, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"ply\"/> but changed its plans when the [[Industrial Development Board for Northern Ireland]] (IDB) offered {{GBP|100 million}} (equivalent to about \u00a3{{inflation|UK|100|1981}}M in {{inflation/year|UK}}) towards it,<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/man.html |work=The DeLorean Museum |title=The man |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210031101/http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/man.html |archivedate=December 10, 2010 }}</ref> despite an assessment by consultants hired by the IDB that the business had only a 1-in-10 chance of success.<ref name=\"ply\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tech.plym.ac.uk/sme/interactive_resources/tutorials/failurecases/fd1.html | work=Failure as a design criterion | title=Failure of Design Management | access-date=February 20, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110213003610/http://www.tech.plym.ac.uk/sme/interactive_resources/tutorials/failurecases/fd1.html | archive-date=February 13, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:1982 De Lorean DMC12 coupe (8453073488).jpg|thumb|1982 DeLorean grey interior]]\nConstruction on the factory began in October 1978, and although production of the DeLorean was scheduled to start in 1979, engineering problems and [[cost overrun|budget overruns]] delayed production until late 1980. By the time production began the unemployment rate was high in Northern Ireland, and local residents lined up to apply for jobs at the factory. The workers were largely inexperienced, but were paid premium wages and supplied with the best equipment available.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ibrahim | first=Jeremy Ethan | title=The Story of John DeLorean - Falling from Grace | website=DriveTribe | date=2020-01-14 | url=https://drivetribe.com/p/the-story-of-john-delorean-falling-HQqcOKf-ScilqBw0Wrum9Q | access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=John DeLorean: A visionary or a charlatan? | website=The Irish Times | date=2013-03-21 | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/john-delorean-a-visionary-or-a-charlatan-1.2488641 | access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nDeLoreans had numerous mechanical problems and suffered from poor build quality. Most quality issues were solved by 1982, and the cars were sold from dealers with a one-year, {{convert|12000|mi|adj=on}} warranty.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.entermyworld.com/cat/dhistory/collectibles/facts-pamphlet/factsj1x1.jpg |website=www.entermyworld.com |title=facts pamphlet (Warranties, Dimensions, Suppliers) |access-date=August 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325051312/http://www.entermyworld.com/cat/dhistory/collectibles/facts-pamphlet/factsj1x1.jpg |archive-date=March 25, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean Motor Company filed [[bankruptcy]] in October 1982<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/26/business/delorean-motor-files-bankruptcy.html</ref>.  Approximately 100 partially assembled DeLoreans on the production line were completed by [[Big Lots|Consolidated International]].  The remaining parts from the factory stock, the parts from the US Warranty Parts Center, as well as parts from the original suppliers that had not yet been delivered to the factory were all shipped to [[Columbus, Ohio]] in 1983\u201384.  A company called KAPAC sold these parts to retail and [[wholesaling|wholesale]] customers by mail order.  In 1997, DeLorean Motor Company of Texas acquired this inventory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/q&a.asp#whereparts |title=DeLorean Motor Company FAQ |publisher=Delorean.com |date=November 6, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121215155/http://delorean.com/q%26a.asp |archivedate=November 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nProduction information was lost or scattered upon the [[DeLorean Motor Company#Downturn and bankruptcy|shutdown of DMC]] and production figures for the DeLorean have never been verified based on official factory records.  Despite some unexplained VIN gaps, based upon VIN information, owners have been able to piece together the approximate quantity of DeLoreans produced.\n\nIn February 1982, DMC was placed into [[receivership]] and the factory continued to operate at a reduced production rate until the end of May.  When Consolidated International acquired the unsold and partially assembled cars in November 1982, it brought back workers to complete the cars remaining on the assembly line. It was decided to make the remaining completed 1982 model year cars into 1983 models. The remaining cars VINs were re-VINed into 1983 cars by taking the original VIN number and adding 5000 to it and changing the \"CD\" in the middle of the VIN to \"DD\" thus making a 1983 model.<ref name=\"Citizen Kidd\"/>\n\nFor the 1981 model year, there were 6,700 DeLoreans produced (VIN 500-7199).  For the 1982 model year, there were 1,999 DeLoreans produced (VIN 10001-11999).  For the 1983 model year, there were 276 DeLoreans (VIN 17000-17170 and 20001-20105) bringing the total estimated production to 8,975 cars.<ref name=\"Citizen Kidd\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.citizenkidd.com/DMC/pages/viN.asp |title=Texas DeLorean Club |access-date=June 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218154415/http://www.citizenkidd.com/DMC/pages/viN.asp |archive-date=December 18, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2007, about 6,500 DeLorean cars were thought to still exist.<ref>{{cite news |first= Martin |last= Zimmerman |url= https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |title= For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |accessdate= January 7, 2013 |work= Los Angeles Times |date= July 28, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130228154343/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |archive-date= February 28, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nThe DeLorean features a number of unusual construction details, including gull-wing doors, unpainted [[stainless-steel]] body panels, and a rear-mounted engine.\n\n===Body===\n[[File:De Lorean DMC-12 at Wollaton Park, Nottingham, England.jpg|thumb|The gull-wing doors on the DeLorean were a distinctive feature.]]\nThe body design of the DeLorean was a product of [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] of [[Italdesign Giugiaro|Ital Design]] and is panelled in brushed [[AISI steel grades#Stainless steel|SS304]] stainless steel. Except for three cars plated in 24-karat gold, all DeLoreans left the factory uncovered by paint or clearcoat.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Body Finish and Composition from Owners Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110228223225/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |archive-date= February 28, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Painted DeLoreans do exist, although these were all painted after the cars were purchased from the factory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |title=DeLorean Prototype & Production |publisher=AACA Museum |date= |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606022652/https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In order to train the workforce, a small number of DeLoreans were produced without the costly stainless steel panels and are referred to as \"black cars\" or \"mules\" in reference to their black fiberglass bodies. These cars were never intended to be sold.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |title=DeLorean - DeLorean DMC-12 Technical (1981-1982) |publisher=Motor-car.net |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425053807/https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSmall scratches in the stainless-steel body panels can be removed with a non-metallic scouring pad (since metal pads can leave iron particles embedded in the stainless steel, which can give the appearance of the stainless \"rusting\"), or even sandpaper.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Care & Feeding: Stainless Steel Body Maintenance |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110515142238/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |archive-date= May 15, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> The stainless-steel panels are fixed to a [[fiberglass]] underbody. The underbody is affixed to a steel double-Y frame chassis, inspired by the [[Lotus Esprit]] platform.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nThe unpainted stainless body creates challenges during [[Automotive restoration|restoration]] of the cars. In traditional automotive body repair, the panel is repaired to be as original (\"straight\") as possible, and imperfections are sculpted back to form with polyester body filler like [[Bondo (putty)|Bondo]] or lead (body [[solder]]). This poses no problem (aside from originality) with most cars, as the filler will be hidden by the car's paint (for example, most new cars have filler hiding the seam where the roof meets the [[quarter panel]]). With an unpainted stainless body, the stainless steel must be reworked to exactly the original shape, contour, and grain, which is a tremendously difficult job on regular steel (a dented or bent panel is stretched, and a shrinking hammer or other techniques must be used to unstretch the metal) and even more difficult with stainless due to its tendency to [[Work hardening|work-harden]]. Furthermore, it is exceedingly difficult to paint stainless steel due to difficulties with paint adhesion. DeLorean envisioned that damaged panels would simply be replaced rather than repaired.\n\nAnother distinctive feature of the DeLorean is its [[gull-wing door]]s. The common problem of supporting the weight of gull-wing doors was solved by other manufacturers with lightweight doors in the [[Mercedes-Benz 300SL]] and a hydraulic pump in the [[Bricklin SV-1]], although these designs had structural or convenience disadvantages. The DeLorean features heavy doors supported by [[Cryogenics|cryogenically]] preset [[Torsion bar suspension|torsion bars]] and gas-charged [[strut]]s.<ref>{{US patent|4,378,658}}</ref> These torsion bars were developed by [[Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation|Grumman Aerospace]] (and built by Unbrako in the UK, a division of SPS Technologies of Jenkintown, Pennsylvania, US) to withstand the stresses of supporting the doors.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Exotic Technology |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511091013/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |archive-date= May 11, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Much like the [[scissor doors|doors]] fitted to the [[Lamborghini Countach]], the DeLorean doors featured small cutout windows, because full-sized windows would not be fully retractable within the short door panels. Additionally, the doors featured red and amber \"safety\" lights around the perimeter. These lights illuminated when the door was open and could be seen from the front, rear or side of the vehicle at night or in low-light situations.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Vehicle Dimensions from Technical Manual, Workshop Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090401070948/http://dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |archive-date= April 1, 2009 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Door Design |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100914111250/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |archive-date= September 14, 2010 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Engine and drivetrain===\nThe [[engine]] is a [[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]] ([[V6 PRV engine|PRV]]) {{cvt|2849|cc|L|2|order=flip}} [[V6 engine|V6]], rated at {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm and [[torque]] of {{convert|153|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 2750 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|website=carfolio.com|title=1981 De Lorean DMC-12 specifications|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614071722/https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1982/587540/de_lorean_dmc-12.html|website=automobile-catalog.com|title=1982 De Lorean DMC-12 specs|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> that was designed and built under special contract with the [[DeLorean Motor Company]]. These PRVs were a development of the 2.7-litre V6 in the [[Renault 30]] and were built in the PRV Factory in [[Douvrin]], Northern France. The 5-speed [[manual transmission]], also designed by PRV, was built at the [[Renault]] facility near [[Caen]] in [[Normandy]]. The engines and [[gearbox]]es were shipped weekly by sea from the PRV factories to the DMC factory.\n\n===Suspension===\nThe [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] is a four-wheel [[independent suspension]], [[coil spring]]s, and telescopic [[shock absorbers]]. The front suspension uses [[Double wishbone suspension|double wishbones]], while the rear is a [[Multi-link suspension|multi-link]] setup.\n\nWhen the DeLorean first arrived in the US, the car had a higher than expected wheel gap in the front suspension.  The nose-high appearance is the result of poor quality coil springs.  Despite having significantly less weight in the front, the front and rear springs had the same spring rate and also used lower quality steel which resulted in the nose-high look.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 | pages = 83}}</ref>  Some people have erroneously cited a last minute change in US bumper height requirements led DMC to raise the vehicle just prior to delivery, however this is not true.  Design drawings clearly show that the design met [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration|NHTSA]] minimum bumper and headlight heights of the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/Bumper/Index.html|title=Bumper Q&A's|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003151011/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/bumper/index.html|archive-date=October 3, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|title=DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 49 CFR Part 571, [Docket No. 01-8885; Notice 01], RIN 2127-AH81, Glare from headlamps and other Front Mounted Lamps, Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard No. 108; Lamps, Reflective Devices, and Associated Equipment|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927155258/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Many owners have subsequently replaced or modified the front springs to return the front height to the original design specification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|title=Improving handling and lowering the DeLorean - DeLorean Motor Company|author=|date=|website=support.delorean.com|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621093431/http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSteering is [[rack and pinion]], with an overall [[steering ratio]] of 14.9:1, giving 2.65 turns lock-to-lock and a {{convert|35|ft|m|adj=on}} turning circle. DeLoreans are fitted with [[alloy|cast alloy]] wheels, measuring {{convert|14|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|6|in|mm}} wide on the front and {{convert|15|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|8|in|mm}} wide on the rear. These were fitted with [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] NCT steel-belted radial tires. The DeLorean is a [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-engine vehicle]] with a 35%\u201365% front\u2013rear weight distribution.<ref>{{cite web|first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_weight.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Weight and Balance from Technical manual |publisher=Dmcnews.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean features power-assisted [[disc brake]]s on all wheels, with {{convert|10|in|mm|adj=on}} rotors front and {{convert|10.5|in|mm|adj=on}} rear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|title=1981 DeLorean-17|author=|date=|website=oldcarbrochures.org|access-date=May 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524222200/http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAt the time of release, the automotive press was generally complimentary towards the DeLorean.  [[Motor Trend]]<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 128\u2013129}}</ref>, [[Car and Driver]] <ref>https://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/comparison-test/a15144078/de-lorean-vs-chevy-corvette-datsun-280-zx-ferrari-308gts-porsche-911-comparison-test/</ref> and [[Road_%26_Track|Road & Track]]<ref>https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/</ref> had mostly positive remarks about the car.  All of them noted disappointing performance especially those that performed comparative tests against other vehicles but were otherwise impressed with the car noting commendable gas mileage most of them noting that the DeLorean is more of a GT car rather than a sports car or racecar.\n\nHowever, more recent reviews of the car have been much more harsh.  [[Time Magazine]] included the DeLorean on its list of 50 worst cars of all time in 2017.<ref>https://time.com/4723114/50-worst-cars-of-all-time/</ref>  In his book ''Naff Motors: 101 Automotive Lemons'', Tony Davis described the build quality as \"woeful\".  ''Top Gear'' writer Richard Porter included it in his book ''Crap Cars'', calling it \"dismal\",<ref name = \"Porter\">{{cite book|last=Porter |first=Richard |title=Crap Cars |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2005 |isbn= |page=}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nDMC's comparison literature noted that the DeLorean could achieve {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|}} in 8.8 seconds, when equipped with a manual transmission. When equipped with an automatic transmission, the DeLorean would accelerate from {{convert|0|to|60|mph|}} in 10.5 seconds as tested by ''Road & Track'' magazine. The car's top speed is {{convert|109|mph|0}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|title=1982 DeLorean DMC-12: The Vintage Road & Track Test|date=October 21, 2015|work=Road & Track|publisher=|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803211950/http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|archive-date=August 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Road and Track called the car: \".. not quick for a sports/GT car in this price category ..\".\n\n==Problems and issues==\nDeLoreans, early production models in particular, suffered from poor build quality as well as mechanical issues with the vehicle.  Early production cars needed as much as 140-200 hours of work at DMC Quality Assurance Centers prior to being shipped to dealerships for delivery. DMC eventually sent 30 factory workers to the quality centers in the US to learn about the issues and how to fix them.  Quality issues did improve over time and by 1982 many of the quality issues had been resolved.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 83 - 84}}</ref>\n\nA total of four recalls were issued by the factory to correct issues such as a sticking throttle, front suspension issues and an inertia switch. <ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 108\u2013109}}</ref>\n\nOther quality issues that plagued the car included other issues surrounding the front suspension, clutch pedal adjustment (or lack thereof), brake rotors, instruments; in particular the [[speedometer]], power door locks and weak alternators.  Many early DeLoreans were delivered with an incorrect alignment with the toe-in incorrectly set leading to premature tire wear. \n\nIn addition, many dealers were reluctant to perform warranty work on DeLoreans since DMC owed them money for past warranty claims that were still unpaid.  Some dealerships were not able to perform repair work properly as DMC never issued a proper service manual.  The lack of quality service at dealerships was a point of frustration for many DeLorean owners at the time, particularly those who paid over sticker price to purchase one of the first cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 111\u2013112}}</ref>\n\n==Pricing and options==\n\nUpon release in 1981, a DeLorean had a suggested retail price of US$25,000 ($650 more when equipped with an [[automatic transmission]]); this is equivalent to approximately US${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|25000|1981}}}} in {{inflation-year|US}}.{{inflation-fn|US}}. MSRP would increase in 1982 to $29,825<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|title=1982 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616231331/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and again in 1983 to $34,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|title=1983 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015225/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> At the outset, there were extensive waiting lists of people willing to pay up to $10,000 above the list price; however, after the collapse of the DeLorean Motor Company, unsold cars could be purchased for less than the retail price.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_sales.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Sales and Dealer Experiences}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean was only available with two factory options; a no-cost [[manual transmission]] or automatic transmission and the choice of a grey or black interior (grey interior became available mid 1981 model year).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |title=one of one! factory burgundy interior delorean |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905044903/https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The standard feature list included stainless-steel body panels; gull-wing doors with cryogenically treated torsion bars; leather seats; [[air conditioning]]; an AM/FM [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] [[stereo system]]; [[power window]]s, [[power door locks|locks]] and [[Power side-view mirror|mirrors]]; a tilt and telescopic [[steering wheel]]; tinted glass; body side moldings; intermittent/constant windshield wipers; and an electric rear-window defogger. Several dealer options were available, including a car cover; [[Sheepskin seat cover|sheepskin]] seat covers; floor mats; car care cleaning kit; black textured accent stripes; grey scotch-cal accent stripes; a luggage rack and a ski-rack adapter.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Dealer Installed Accessories |date= June 20, 1981 |access-date= January 27, 2005 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/6HxeVWMtL?url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |archive-date= July 8, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |title= DeLorean Owners Association: DeLorean specifications table |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980214030500/http://delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |archivedate=February 14, 1998}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=390 | image1=DMC Sticker.jpg |width1=199 |height1=260 |alt1=1982 DMC-12 window sticker |image2=DMC12 clearance.jpg |width2=200 |height2=260 |alt2=DeLorean clearance advertisement |footer_align=center |footer=1982 window sticker & 1983 DeLorean clearance advertisement}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Production changes==\nAlthough there were no typical yearly updates to the DeLorean, several changes were made to the DeLorean during production.<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\"/>  Instead of making changes at the end of the model year, DMC implemented changes mid-production. This resulted in no clear distinction between the 1981, 1982, and 1983 model years, but with subtle changes taking place almost continuously throughout the life cycle of the DeLorean.\n\n===Hood styles===\nThe original [[hood (vehicle)|hood]] of the DeLorean had [[Groove (machining)|grooves]] running down both sides. It included a tank flap to simplify [[Filling station|fuel filling]]. These cars typically had a locking cap to prevent fuel theft by [[siphon]]ing. In August 1981, the hood flap was removed from the hood of the cars (although the hood creases remained). This style was retained well into 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |title=The DeLorean |publisher=Babb Technology |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=November 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Based on production numbers for all three years, this hood style is probably the most common. After the supply of locking caps was exhausted, the company switched to a non-locking version (resulting in at least 500 cars with no flap, but with locking caps). The final styling for the hood included the addition of a DeLorean name badge and the removal of the grooves, resulting in a completely flat hood. According to senior personnel who worked at the Dunmurry factory, initial elimination of flapped hoods has a simple if unglamorous explanation; Chuck Benington, managing director, did not like the design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Sutton, Purchasing Manager, Dunmurry factory|url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132250/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|archive-date=April 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=600 |image1=Early 1981 De Lorean hood.jpg |width1=387 |height1=142 |alt1=Early 1981 hood |image2=1983 De Lorean hood.jpg |width2=414 |height2=162 |alt2=1983 hood |footer_align=center |footer=Side-by-side comparison of an early 1981 hood (left) vs. a later model 1983 hood (right)}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Other changes===\n[[File:De Lorean add-on Pull strap.jpg|thumb|Early pull strap]]\n[[File:Delorean dmc-12 later style side bolster.jpg|thumb|Later-style one-piece bolster]]\n[[File:mid 1981 De Lorean silver wheel.JPG|thumb|Mid-1981 silver wheel]]\n\nJohn DeLorean was {{height|ft=6|in=4}} tall, and he designed the car to comfortably fit someone of his stature.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|title= The DeLorean's Time Leap|author= Claire Suddath|publisher= [[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date= April 19, 2012|access-date= July 14, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140706011419/http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|archive-date= July 6, 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> For shorter people, the addition of a pull strap made closing the doors much easier from the inside. These attach to the existing door handle. Late-model 1981 cars, and all cars from 1982 and 1983, have doors with integrated pull straps.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\">{{cite web|url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|title=DeLorean \u2013 The Car: Production Changes|work=babbtechnology.com|access-date=August 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe side [[bolster]]ing in the DeLorean was originally separate from the main interior pieces. In cars with this construction, is a tendency to place pressure on this piece when entering and exiting the vehicle, which eventually causes the bolstering to separate from the trim panel. To solve this problem, cars built in and after late 1981 have one solid trim piece with the bolster permanently attached.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nAs an addition to later cars, a foot rest, or [[dead pedal]], was added to help prevent [[fatigue (physical)|fatigue]] while driving. This is one of the few changes that is directly tied to a model year. These were built into only a few of the late-1981 vehicles and were added to all cars starting with 1982 production.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\"/>\n\nAlthough the styling of the DeLorean's wheels remained unchanged, the wheels of early-model 1981 vehicles were painted grey. These wheels sported matching grey centre caps with an embossed DMC logo. Early into the 1981 production run, these were changed to a polished silver look, with a contrasting black center cap. The embossed logo on the center caps was painted silver to add contrast.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the DeLorean came with an AM/FM stereo radio with cassette made by Craig. Since the Craig radio did not have a built-in clock, one was installed in front of the [[gear shift]] on the console. DeLorean switched to an ASI stereo in the middle of the 1982 production run. Since the ASI radio featured an on-board clock, the clock on the console was removed at the same time.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 44\u201345}}</ref>\n\nThe first 2,200 cars produced used a windshield-embedded [[antenna (radio)|antenna]]. This type of antenna proved to be unsuitable with poor radio reception. Oftentimes the radio would continually \"seek\", attempting to find a signal. A standard whip antenna, which was later changed to a manually retractable antenna, was added to the outside of the front right fender. While improving radio reception, this resulted in a hole in the stainless steel, and an unsightly antenna. As a result, the antenna was again moved. The final antenna was an automatic retractable version installed under the rear induction grill behind the rear driver's-side window.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 28\u201329}}</ref>\n\nThe small [[visor|sun visors]] on the DeLorean have [[Polyvinyl chloride|vinyl]] on one side and headliner [[Textile|fabric]] on the other side. Originally these were installed such that the headliner side would be on the bottom when not in use. Later on in 1981, they were reversed so that the vinyl side would be on the bottom.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 40}}</ref>\n\nThe original 80 amp Ducellier [[Alternator (auto)|alternator]] supplied with the early-production DeLoreans could not provide enough [[electric current|current]] to supply the car when all lights and electrical options were on; as a result, the [[battery (electricity)|battery]] would gradually discharge, leaving the driver stranded on the road. Beginning with cars built in late 1981, DeLoreans were fitted from the factory with a 90 amp [[Motorola]] alternator, which solved this problem. Additional battery drainage problems were caused by faulty or improperly adjusted door jamb switches. This switch activated the \"safety\" lights located around the door perimeter when it was open. When the door was closed, the door seals prevented the light from being seen. Due to the faulty switches the lights remained on, draining the battery. This happened to DeLorean owner [[Johnny Carson]] shortly after he was presented with the vehicle.\n\n==Notable and unique DeLoreans==\n\n===Prototypes and pilot cars===\nOnly one of two DeLorean prototypes still exists.<ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |publisher=DeLorean PJ Grady Europe |title=Delorean Repairs |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421053458/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Prototype 1 sold at the bankruptcy auction in 1984 for $37,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |title=DeLorean prototype cars sell at auction for total $58,000 |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602233213/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The car remained in a private collection until 2005 when it was sold to the owner of DeLorean Motor Company of Florida (DMCFL) where it received a complete restoration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |title=1587: 1976 DeLorean DMC-12 Original Prototype |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602234250/https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Proto 1 is now on display at DMCFL. Proto 2 was sent to [[Lotus Cars]] for development and evaluation in 1978. It was reported to have been destroyed in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Car |url=http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |website=The Delorean Museum |publisher=The Delorean Museum |accessdate=October 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006112343/http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |archivedate=October 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 28 pilot cars were built by DMC. The pilot cars are best identified by the subtly different interiors and sliding side windows. These cars, used for evaluation and regulatory testing of the DeLorean, were previously thought to have been destroyed. Subsequently, several of the pilot cars were found to have survived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |title=Earliest known Pilot car found/photographed |publisher=Dmctalk.org |date=November 5, 1955 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132601/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |archive-date=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |title=Pilot Chronology |publisher=Pjgrady.co.uk |date=November 24, 1980 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051421/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Pilot car 25 which was featured on the front cover of [[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]] in 1981 was found in 2003 in a barn in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |title=pilot-25 |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905040305/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Visioneering car===\nWith the 1980 [[National Automobile Dealers Association|NADA]] meeting approaching, DMC planned to show a final \u201cproduction\u201d version of the DeLorean, however there were no production cars ready at the time or even any production stainless steel panels.\n\nEarlier, in the summer of 1979, the revised Giugiaro styling mock-up was shipped to Visioneering, a [[Detroit]] based company, to create data needed to make the stamping dies for the stainless panels. This project would expand to create dies used to create a \u201cproduction\u201d car for the NADA show.\n\nUsing a prototype chassis supplied by Lotus in late 1979, Visioneering completed the assembly of this car at a cost of $750,000. The car was presented at the 1980 NADA show and was later used for engineering development and technical training as well as press photos. The Visioneering car would eventually be sold at the bankruptcy auction in late 1984 for $21,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\"/> Today, the car is in a private collection.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage| ISBN = 978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2012 | page = 108}}</ref>\n\n===Legend turbo cars===\nIt was determined that the DeLorean needed additional power when automotive magazine road tests showed {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|abbr=on}} times for the DeLorean between 9.5 and 10.5 seconds, while its rivals were in the 7.5\u20138.5 second range. There had been interest in [[turbocharger|turbocharging]] the DeLorean early on, but the DMC engineering staff was busy with other projects, so DeLorean decided to go outside to develop a turbocharged version of the DeLorean.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\">{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion | isbn=0-9744141-0-7 | author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |date= 2003 | pages = 110\u2013111}}</ref>\n\nHaving had previous success with turbocharging [[Fiat 124 Sport Spider|Fiat Spiders]], DeLorean entered into a contract with Legend Industries, based in [[Hauppauge, New York|Hauppauge]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. DMC wanted to increase power without sacrificing fuel efficiency. DMC wanted a wide power band and did not want a surge of power similar to the [[Porsche 930]] Turbo. Legend used twin [[IHI Corporation|IHI]] RHB52 turbos along with twin [[intercooler]]s. The results were an engine capable of accelerating smoothly in fifth gear from 1,500&nbsp;rpm to full turbo boost at 2,500&nbsp;rpm, reaching {{convert|150|mph|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\" />\n[[File:Legend engine.jpg|thumb|Legend Twin Turbo setup from VIN 530]]\n\nIn addition, Legend Industries developed a single turbocharged setup that was never finished.\nThe company converted a total of four DeLoreans and two Renault Alpines, which were the first development cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|title=Delorean Car Sales Europe UK. Canvey Island Essex SS8 OPQ|publisher=|access-date=February 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513040331/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|archive-date=May 13, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[VIN]] 530 was written in numerous press articles as the fastest production car of its era.\n\nIn a test run of VIN 530 at [[Bridgehampton Race Circuit|Bridgehampton Raceway]] in 1981, the twin-turbo DeLorean was quicker than a [[Ferrari 308 GTB/GTS|Ferrari 308]] and a [[Porsche 928]]. It has been a misconception for many years that VIN 502 was at Bridgehampton and used in testing; however, evidence from pictures, along with information from a Legend employee published by PJ Grady, indicates that 530 was used along with VIN 558.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |title=identifying-the-legend-cars |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905041236/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By the time of Bridgehampton, Legend had perfected modular boosting, which the earlier prototypes did not have installed apart from one of the Alpine mules and VIN 530.<ref>{{cite web | title=DeLorean DMC-12 | website=Silodrome | date=March 3, 2018 | url=https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | access-date=September 5, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905042552/https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | archive-date=September 5, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVIN 530 tested 0\u201360&nbsp;mph in 5.8 seconds and the [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] in 14.7 seconds. John DeLorean was so impressed with the engine, he committed to ordering 5,000 engines from Legend Industries. DMC planned to offer a turbocharged engine as a $7,500 option in 1984 (presumably to compete with the newly redesigned [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|1984 Corvette]]). Before any of the 5,000 cars could be put into production, DMC had declared bankruptcy, which drove Legend Industries, as well as other suppliers, into bankruptcy.<ref name=\"DeLorean Gold Portfolio\">{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Gold Portfolio | author=R. M. Clarke| publisher = Brookland Books LTD. |ISBN=1-85520-331-6 |date= 1996 | pages = 137\u2013143}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" Style=\"text-align:center\"\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n!\tVIN\t!!\tConfiguration\t!!\tLast known location\t!!\tComments\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t502\t||\tTwin\t||\tNew Zealand\t||\tOriginal prototype\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t528\t||\tSingle\t||\tNew York\t||\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t530\t||\tTwin\t||\tUnited Kingdom\t||\tSister twin-turbo\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t558\t||\tSingle\t||\tUnknown\t||\t\n|}\n\n===Gold-plated===\n[[File:gold-D.jpg|thumb|A gold-plated DeLorean in Reno, Nevada]]\nFor Christmas 1980, a DeLorean/[[American Express]] promotion planned to sell 100 [[Karat|24K]]-[[Gilding|gold-plated]] DeLoreans for US$85,000 each to its gold-card members, but only two were sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|title=In 1980, You Could Buy an $85,000, 24K-Gold-Plated DeLorean|publisher=|access-date=September 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920152935/http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> One of these was purchased by Roger Mize, president of Snyder National Bank in [[Snyder, Texas]]. VIN #4301 sat in the bank lobby for over 20 years before being loaned to the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]] in [[Los Angeles]]. It has a black interior and an automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |title=The 24-Karat Gold Plated DeLorean Car |publisher=Bigtexas.com |accessdate=January 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224111825/http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe second gold-plated American Express DeLorean was purchased by Sherwood Marshall, an entrepreneur and former [[Royal Canadian Navy|Royal Canadian Naval]] Officer. Marshall donated his DeLorean to the [[William F. Harrah]] Foundation/[[National Automobile Museum]] in [[Reno, Nevada]]. This car, VIN #4300, is the only one of the three existing gold-plated cars to be equipped with a manual transmission. It has a saddle-brown interior and, like its golden siblings, is a low-mileage vehicle with only {{convert|1442|mi}} on the [[odometer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.automuseum.org |title=National Automobile Museum |publisher=National Automobile Museum |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207005657/http://www.automuseum.org/ |archive-date=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA third gold-plated car exists with {{convert|636|mi}} on the odometer; it carries the VIN plate for the last DeLorean, #20105, although final assembly was actually completed in Columbus, Ohio, in 1983.<ref name=bigtexas>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Gold DeLorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Bigtexas.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110812111029/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/|archivedate=August 12, 2011 }}</ref> This car was assembled with spare parts that were required by American Express in case one of the other two that were built were damaged and all necessary gold-plated parts were on hand, with the exception of one door. Thus the car was assembled after another door was gold-plated, though the added door does not precisely match the rest of the car in color and grain. The car was first acquired by the winner of a [[Big Lots]] store raffle. Consolidated International, which owned the department store, had purchased 1374 DeLoreans during the DeLorean Motor Company's financial troubles, acquiring the remaining stock after the company went into receivership. Now held by a private owner in [[La Vale, Maryland]], this third and last gold-plated DeLorean was for sale online at a price of US$250,000, but remains unsold.<ref name=bigtexas/> After being offered for sale for over a decade, it is unclear whether it has sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Delorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Archive.is |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524094241/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |archivedate=May 24, 2012 }}</ref> This car and the example in Reno have saddle-brown leather interiors, a color scheme which was intended to become an option on later-production cars, however, these two cars were the only DeLoreans to ever be equipped with these factory parts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://support.delorean.com/kb/a10/interior-colors-carpets-and-parts.aspx |title=interior-colors-carpets-and-parts |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905043350/http://support.delorean.com/kb/a10/interior-colors-carpets-and-parts.aspx |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA gold-plated DeLorean was reproduced privately by an enthusiast.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |title=Gold Plated DeLoreans? \u2013 Yes There Were Four |publisher=Mycarquest.com |date=February 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051720/http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |archive-date=April 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Right-hand-drive models===\nDeLoreans were primarily intended for the American market. All production models were therefore [[left-hand-drive]]. Evidence survives from as early as April 1981, however, that the DeLorean Motor Company was aware of the need to produce a [[right-hand-drive]] (RHD) version to supply to world markets, specifically the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |title=woller-hodec |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905043041/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company faced the choice of building right-hand-drive models from scratch or performing a post-production conversion exercise. Given the cost of new body molds, tooling, and a host of specific parts that a factory-built right-hand-drive configuration would require, the company opted to investigate the idea of a post-production conversion using a UK company based in [[Hampshire]] called Wooler-Hodec Ltd.<ref>{{cite book | last=Narus | first=D. | title=Independent Sports Cars | publisher=Lulu.com | year=2017 | isbn=978-1-387-15601-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HolUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA48 | access-date=August 30, 2019 | page=48}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[File:De Lorean DMC12 - Flickr - foshie (1).jpg|thumb|RHD DeLorean]]\nOnly 16 right-hand-drive factory-authorized DeLoreans were ever produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |title=DeLorean: Euro Spec DeLoreans |publisher=Deloreans.co.uk |accessdate=May 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617185502/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010 }}</ref> These cars can be divided into two distinct groups:\n# The first batch, known by enthusiasts as the \"Wooler-Hodec cars\", were converted by the UK company of that name. Evidence still exists in the form of a DMC factory memo, which orders 20 cars to be converted to right-hand drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |title=DMC Inter-Office Memo: RHD Conversion Programme |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905045408/https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to the factory's closure, this order was never completed, and today a total of 13 cars survive, carrying the VINs 510, 12171\u201312181 and 12199. VIN 510 is understood to be the first of this batch of cars converted and was later sold at the factory auction in 1984. The other 12 cars were auctioned off by the receivers in early 1983. As a result, several of these cars were registered at the same time and have the Northern Irish registration (license) number \"SIJ xxxx\". All of this first batch of cars had a black interior and all had manual transmission, except VIN 12175. This car is the only factory-authorized right-hand-drive black-interior automatic car and is owned by Andrew Withers, former editor of the UK DeLorean Owners Club.\n# The second batch were registered and used by the factory in Northern Ireland, with registration numbers (license plates), AXI 1697, AXI 1698, AXI 1699 and are referred to by enthusiasts as the \"AXI cars\". These three cars (VINs 5565, 5592 and 5638) differ from the first Wooler-Hodec cars in several ways. They all had roof-mounted radio antennas, indicator repeater lights, no side marker lights, white forward-facing door lights, fog-light switch, and textured body rubstrips on the stainless panels. No [[catalytic converters]] or [[Oxygen sensor|lambda equipment]] were fitted, as British legislation did not require them. VIN 5565 with the registration number AXI 1697 was a fully UK homologated example, which was shown at the British motor show at Birmingham, UK in October 1982. It includes a unique rearward-facing twin exhaust, no catalytic converters and the UK-specification engine as used by Volvo, but retaining the usual Renault ancillaries. The transmission final drive was also set at 3.88:1 versus the standard 3.44:1. Attention was paid to other unique details such as correctly offset wing mirrors.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nA common misconception surrounding the factory-authorized right-hand-drive DeLoreans is that they were all fitted with different, so-called \"Euro-spec\", tail lights<ref name=\"rubberlight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating so-called \"Euro-spec\" tail light unit |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223141/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> as part of the right-hand-drive conversion program. This is not the case. Due to the nature of these cars as prototypes, they were not officially type-approved for use in the UK. Owners who bought these cars at auction in the early 1980s encountered difficulty in registering them as new vehicles in the UK. At this point a former DeLorean Motor Cars executive offered to modify and register the cars so that they could be used in the UK. These modifications included:\n* Different seat-belt units fitted.<ref name=\"foglight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified seat belt unit in right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223213/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of Rubbolite tail light clusters with a built-in fog light function.<ref name=\"rubberlight\"/>\n* The fitting of a fog light switch to one of the center-console dummy switches.<ref name=\"foglight\"/>\n* A custom-made tail light surround and number (license) plate bezel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating custom fabricated tail light and number (license) plate bezel fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223225/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the front turn signal lenses for ones of a different, more rounded style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating rounded turn signal lens on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013912/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the rear side marker lenses for amber ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating amber rear side marker lens fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223301/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThere were a number of official alterations made to the right-hand-drive cars' lights. The extent of these modifications varies between the first batch of \"Wooler-Hodec\" cars and the later \"AXI\" cars:\n\nAll of the 13 Wooler-Hodec cars were modified to the OEM front turn-signal lens fixing method in order to make them fit flush with the front fascia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified front turn signal lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013859/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref> The cars' headlights were also changed for right-hand-drive spec lights that incorporate a UK sidelight feature. The rest of the lights appear to have been left untouched by Wooler-Hodec during the conversion process.\n\nBy contrast, the three AXI cars had further modifications to the amber front door lights, which were exchanged for clear lenses of the same style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating clear door light lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223348/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> Perhaps the most significant alteration on the AXI cars is the deletion of the front and rear side markers. These are replaced by a single small round European-style indicator side repeater, situated on the front wing (fender). The body rubstrips are also of a different configuration in order to cover the areas that would otherwise have had federal side marker lenses fitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified rubstrips and single round marker light |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223415/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===''Back to the Future''===\n{{Main|DeLorean time machine}}\n[[File:'81-'82 DeLorean DMC-12.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean \"time machine\" from the ''Back to the Future'' trilogy exhibited at [[Universal Studios Florida]]]]\nSeveral special-edition DeLorean cars have been produced over the years, and the car is most notably featured as the time machine in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' film trilogy]]. Six DeLorean chassis were used during the production, along with one manufactured out of fiberglass for scenes where a full-size DeLorean was needed to \"fly\" on-screen; only three of the cars still exist, with one that was destroyed at the end of ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]'', two additional cars were abandoned, and the fiberglass replica was scrapped. Universal Studios owns two of the remaining cars, occasionally putting them on display or using them for other productions, and the last resides in a private collection after having been extensively restored.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |title=BTTF3 DeLorean: Where Are They? |date= |accessdate=January 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005125859/http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |archive-date=October 5, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The official ''[[Back to the Future]]'' DeLorean can be viewed at the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |title=Petersen Automotive Museum |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320133259/http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |archivedate=March 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA number of production DeLoreans have been modified by the [[Automotive aftermarket|aftermarket]] into ''Back to the Future'' time machine replicas, whose bodies and interiors are modified to mirror the appearance and functions of the film cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|title=Bob's Prop Shop|work=bobspropshop.com|access-date=November 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016005640/http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|archive-date=October 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==DMC Texas==\n[[File:\" 12 - ITALY (Milan) Electro Vehicles Europe ( EVE ) DeLorean DMC-12.JPG|thumb|[[Electric car|All-electric model]] DMCev in Milan (2012)]]\nIn 1995, Stephen Wynne from Liverpool created a separate company based in Texas using the [[DeLorean Motor Company (Texas)|DeLorean Motor Company]] name. Wynne acquired the trademark on the stylized DMC logo, along with the remaining parts inventory of the original DeLorean Motor Company. The company rebuilds cars at its [[Humble, Texas]], location using a combination of [[new old stock]] (NOS) parts, original equipment manufacturer (OEM), and reproduction parts on a made-to-order basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103728/http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archivedate=July 18, 2011|title=New build cars|publisher=DeLorean Motor Company|accessdate=May 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDMC Texas (based in [[Humble, Texas]]) announced on July 30, 2007, that the car would be returning into very limited production (about 20 cars a year) in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |title=For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |work=LA Times |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310115947/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |archive-date=March 10, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> They were subsequently sued by John DeLorean's widow for illegally licensing the family name. DMC Texas settled this lawsuit in September 2015 by paying his widow an undisclosed sum and in turn received rights to use the name, images, and trademark in the future.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lawyers Settle DeLorean Lawsuit Just in Time for 'Back to the Future' Day|url = https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|website = WSJ Blogs \u2013 Law Blog|date = October 21, 2015|accessdate = December 26, 2015|first = Jacob|last = Gershman|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222085854/http://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|archive-date = December 22, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe cars were announced to have a new stainless-steel frame; with optional extras such as GPS, an enhanced \"Stage 2\" engine, and possibly a new modern interior. Given that the cars were made with 80% old parts,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |title=Texas Entrepreneur Set to Start Building DeLorean Cars |publisher=Fox News |date=August 21, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511132411/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |archive-date=May 11, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> the term \"return to production\" is something of a misnomer; the cars are constructed on DeLorean underbodies built by the original company in the 1980s and retaining their VINs. The cars' titles show the year of the underbody's manufacture. Therefore, they are not new DeLoreans, but complete rebuilds of the car from the underbody with enhancements. In 2009, the price of a refurbished DeLorean from DMC Texas started at US$57,500, and the project was featured in an episode of ''[[Modern Marvels]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|title=Anything But Rusty: Reviewing The DeLorean In 2009|first=Ryan|last=McCaffrey|publisher=Motor Authority|date=December 20, 2009|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222115538/http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2011, it was announced that an all-electric model would be available for sale by 2013. It was said to have a {{Convert|200|hp|0|abbr=on|adj=on}} motor, accelerate from {{Convert|0|to|60|mph|abbr=on|km/h}} in 8 seconds, and sell for US$90,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Fox News |date=October 18, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029024300/http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archivedate=October 29, 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |title=The New DeLorean EV Gets Some Test Runs by Enthusiasts |work=Automotive Discovery |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026195129/http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |archive-date=October 26, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Back To The Future: All Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Forbes |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101212905/http://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archive-date=November 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Initial test drives revealed that the prototype had a range of {{Convert|70|mi|km}}, approaching the {{Convert|100|mi|km}} that was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|title=Electric DeLorean: First Drive|first=Kevin|last=McCauley|publisher=Jalopnik|date=October 17, 2011|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025045755/http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|archive-date=October 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> However, 2014 saw criticism from fans who tried to buy the electric DeLorean only to learn that it was still unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|title=It Seems DeLorean Has Gone Back To The Past Again|first=Wes|last=Lungwitz|publisher=Car Debater|date=February 14, 2014|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106215825/http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|archive-date=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDue to the passage of the [[Low Volume Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Act of 2015|Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act]], DMC Texas announced that it would be producing replica DeLoreans with an expected release date in 2017. DMC anticipated building approximately 50 vehicles per year over six years with an estimated retail price of US$100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |title=The DeLorean Is Coming Back Thanks To This New Law, Will Have 300-400 HP |first=Jason |last=Torchinsky |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830195816/https://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |title=Brand-New DeLorean Replicas Are on the Way |date=January 27, 2016 |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914085258/https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |archive-date=September 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2016, DMC announced that it was expecting to build 12 units in the first production year with as many as 50 in the second year of production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |title=DMC Blog - DeLorean - The New DMC DeLorean |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827145747/http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |archive-date=August 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>   In December 2019, the NHTSA issued guidelines for the Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act<ref>https://www.nhtsa.gov/sites/nhtsa.dot.gov/files/documents/replica_vehicle_program_nprm_12172019.pdf</ref> and DMC Texas is now projecting they will begin production in 2021.<ref>https://www.autoblog.com/2020/01/24/delorean-motor-company-dmc-12-new-cars/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<!-- Dead note \"production2\": [http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/img/news/n_vinrat.pdf DMC-12 Estimated Production Volumes by Month] (PDF) by Knut Grimsrud -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/index.html DMC - The legend - DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean.hu/ - Delorean Club Hungary- DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |first1= John Z. |last1= DeLorean |first2= Ted |last2= Schwarz |title= DeLorean |location= Grand Rapids, MI |publisher= Zondervan |year= 1985 |isbn= 0-310-37940-7 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/delorean00delo }}\n* {{cite book |first= John |last= Lamm |title= DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion |edition= 2nd |year= 2003 |location= Fort Jones, CA |publisher= Red Lion Press |isbn= 0-9744141-0-7}}\n* {{cite book |first= R. M. |last= Clarke |title= DeLorean: 1977\u20131995 Gold Portfolio |year= 1995 |location= Cobham |publisher= Brooklands |isbn= 1-85520-331-6}}\n* {{cite book |first= James |last= Espey |title= The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | edition= 2nd |year= 2014 |publisher= the DeLorean Garage |isbn= 978-0-9856578-1-9}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris | last= Parnham |first2= Andrew | last2= Withers |title= DeLorean Celebrating the Impossible |year= 2015| location = | publisher= DeLorean Motor Cars (1978) Ltd.| ISBN= 978-0-9928594-0-4}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris |last= Williams|title= DeLorean DMC-12 [sic], The Essential Buyers Guide (2018) |year=2018 | location= |publisher= Veloce Publishing| ISBN=9 78-1-787112-32-2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia |\n | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n | |\n | Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED. |\n | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details. |\n | |\n | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or |\n | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org) |\n | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template. |\n==={{No more links}}=========-->\n\n{{Commons category|DeLorean DMC-12}}\n* [http://www.delorean.com/ DeLorean Motor Company]\n* {{curlie|Recreation/Autos/Makes_and_Models/DeLorean/|DeLorean DMC-12}}\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=De Lorean|model=DMC