{"title_page": "Western New Mexico Aviation Heritage Museum", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox museum\n|name= Western New Mexico Aviation Heritage Museum\n|image=  \n|alt= \n|imagesize= \n|map_type= New Mexico\n|map_caption= \n|coordinates = {{coord|35.166513|-107.898221|display=inline}}\n|established= 2012<ref name=beacon>{{cite news|last=Boyett|first=Rosanne|title=More than eight decades of history|url=http://www.cibolabeacon.com/cibola_living/more-than-eight-decades-of-history/article_f2941b84-b405-11e1-8925-001a4bcf887a.html|accessdate=27 July 2013|newspaper=Cibola County Beacon|date=12 June 2012}}</ref>\n|location= \n|visitors= \n|director= \n|publictransit = \n|website= {{url|www.cibolahistory.org/airway-heritage-museum.html}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Western New Mexico Aviation Heritage Museum''' is a small aviation museum located at the Grants-Milan airport (KGNT) in [[Grants, New Mexico]].  It was dedicated on June 9, 2012<ref name=beacon/>  It commemorates the Los Angeles to Amarillo segment of the [[Transcontinental Air Transport]], an early air mail provider.  It consists of a lighted tower, a small building with a generator, and a concrete arrow which helped aviators find the correct direction to continue in.<ref>{{cite web|title=What are these Giant Concrete Arrows across the American Landscape|url=http://www.core77.com/blog/transportation/what_are_these_giant_concrete_arrows_across_the_american_landscape_25236.asp|work=18 July 2013|publisher=core 77|accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cibolahistory.org/airway-heritage-museum.html official site]\n\n[[Category:History museums in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Museums in Cibola County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Aerospace museums in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Grants, New Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Museum\n|name= Western New Mexico Aviation Heritage Museum\n|image=  \n|alt= \n|imagesize= \n|map_type= New Mexico\n|map_caption= \n|coordinates = {{coord|35.166513|-107.898221|display=inline}}\n|established= 2012<ref name=beacon>{{cite news|last=Boyett|first=Rosanne|title=More than eight decades of history|url=http://www.cibolabeacon.com/cibola_living/more-than-eight-decades-of-history/article_f2941b84-b405-11e1-8925-001a4bcf887a.html|accessdate=27 July 2013|newspaper=Cibola County Beacon|date=12 June 2012}}</ref>\n|location= \n|visitors= \n|director= \n|publictransit = \n|website= {{url|www.cibolahistory.org/airway-heritage-museum.html}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Western New Mexico Aviation Heritage Museum''' is a small aviation museum located at the Grants-Milan airport (KGNT) in [[Grants, New Mexico]].  It was dedicated on June 9, 2012<ref name=beacon/>  It commemorates the Los Angeles to Amarillo segment of the [[Transcontinental Air Transport]], an early air mail provider.  It consists of a lighted tower, a small building with a generator, and a concrete arrow which helped aviators find the correct direction to continue in.<ref>{{cite web|title=What are these Giant Concrete Arrows across the American Landscape|url=http://www.core77.com/blog/transportation/what_are_these_giant_concrete_arrows_across_the_american_landscape_25236.asp|work=18 July 2013|publisher=core 77|accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cibolahistory.org/airway-heritage-museum.html official site]\n\n[[Category:History museums in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Museums in Cibola County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Aerospace museums in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Grants, New Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, addedunderlinkedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_New_Mexico_Aviation_Heritage_Museum"}
